const QUIZ_INPUTS = [{"id": "stage-0", "title": "Start Here: One Tool, Many Front-ends", "concepts": ["Claude Code", "shared config"], "claims": ["Claude Code's terminal CLI and the Desktop app 'Code' tab are the same engine reading the same config (CLAUDE.md, MCP, hooks, skills, settings).", "Claude Code vs Codex is not either/or; the productive pattern is to run both."], "content": "## Why the names blur — and why that's good news\nYou've been asked to stand up \"Claude\" for your team, and the vocabulary already fights you. There's a **Desktop app** with a tab called *Code*, a **terminal command** called `claude`, a cloud thing called **Cowork**, and a separate vendor's tool called **Codex**. People in your channel use these words interchangeably and inconsistently, and the docs don't always disambiguate them either.\n\nHere is the load-bearing fact that makes the rest of this course tractable:\n\n> **Claude Code's terminal CLI and the Desktop app's *Code* tab are the same engine reading the same config** — the same `CLAUDE.md`, MCP servers, hooks, skills, and settings. (Source: https://code.claude.com/docs/en/desktop-quickstart)\n\nThe official quickstart puts it plainly: *\"Desktop runs the same engine as the CLI with a graphical interface. You can run both simultaneously on the same project, and they share configuration (CLAUDE.md files, MCP servers, hooks, skills, and settings).\"*\n\nThat is the whole insight of stage 0. You are not configuring four products. You are configuring **one product** — Claude Code — and the front-ends are interchangeable windows onto it. When your teammate on macOS uses the GUI and your teammate on Linux uses the terminal, they drive the same engine off the same files in the repo. That is what makes a *team* setup possible: you write the config once, commit it, and every face of the tool obeys it.\n\nThe rest of this stage names each face precisely, shows you the config files they all share (with real, copy-able formats and exact paths), and draws the one genuine boundary that *isn't* just a UI difference: Codex, a different vendor's agent that does not read Claude's config and is a deliberate complement, not a substitute.\n\n## What \"Claude Code\" actually is\n**Claude Code is Anthropic's agentic coding tool**: a long-running agent that reads your repository, plans, edits files, runs commands, and iterates — driven either from a terminal or a GUI. \"Agentic\" is the operative word. It is not a chat box that emits code for you to paste. It holds a session, takes tools (read file, write file, run bash, call an MCP server), and works in a loop until the task is done or it needs you.\n\n### One engine, multiple front-ends\n\nMentally, separate two layers:\n\n- **The engine** — the agent loop, the tool-use machinery, the model calls, and the *config resolver* that loads your instructions, permissions, MCP servers, hooks, and skills at session start.\n- **The front-end** — the surface you sit in front of: a terminal TUI, a Desktop GUI pane, an IDE side panel, or a web/cloud session.\n\nThe engine is the same across front-ends. The front-end only changes ergonomics. The terminal gives you keyboard-driven speed and easy scripting; the Desktop GUI adds a sidebar of parallel sessions (each in its own git worktree), drag-and-drop panes (chat, diff, terminal, file editor, preview), visual diff review with line-level comments, live app preview, and GitHub PR monitoring with auto-merge. Neither changes *what the agent can do* or *which config it reads*.\n\n### Why this matters for a team lead\n\nIf the engine and config are shared, then your job — \"set up Claude for the team\" — collapses to **authoring shared config files and committing them**. You do not onboard people per-surface. A `CLAUDE.md` you commit today is read identically whether a teammate runs `claude` in a tmux pane or clicks the Code tab in the Desktop app. Get the files right once and the surface choice becomes a personal-preference detail, not an infrastructure decision.\n\nOne practical note from the quickstart: the Desktop app *bundles* Claude Code — you don't need to install Node.js or the CLI separately to use the Code tab. If you also want the `claude` terminal command, you install the CLI separately. Same engine either way.\n\n## The five faces, mapped\nHere are the names you'll hear, what each actually *is*, and whether it shares Claude Code's config.\n\n| Name | What it is | Engine | Reads shared Claude config? | Runs where |\n|------|-----------|--------|------------------------------|-----------|\n| **Claude Code CLI** (`claude`) | Terminal TUI; the canonical surface | Claude Code | Yes | Local (your machine) |\n| **Desktop → Code tab** | GUI front-end on the *same* engine | Claude Code | Yes | Local, Remote (Anthropic cloud), or SSH |\n| **Desktop → Cowork tab** | Autonomous background agent in a cloud VM | Claude Code (remote) | Yes (same infra as Claude Code on the web) | Cloud VM |\n| **Desktop → Chat tab** | claude.ai-style chat, **no file access** | Not the coding agent | No | n/a |\n| **OpenAI Codex** | A *different vendor's* agentic coding tool | Codex (OpenAI) | **No** — reads `AGENTS.md` + `~/.codex/config.toml` | Local CLI, IDE ext, Codex Cloud |\n\nThe Desktop app, per the quickstart, has exactly three tabs: *\"**Chat**: General conversation with no file access, similar to claude.ai. **Cowork**: An autonomous background agent that works on tasks in a cloud VM with its own environment. **Code**: An interactive coding assistant with direct access to your local files.\"* (Source: https://code.claude.com/docs/en/desktop-quickstart)\n\n### Reading the table\n\nThe first three rows are *the same tool*. Within the Code tab itself you pick where it runs — **Local** (your files directly), **Remote** (Anthropic's cloud infrastructure, sessions continue even if you close the app, same infra as Claude Code on the web), or **SSH** (your own server / VM / dev container; Desktop installs Claude Code on the remote machine automatically the first time). The **Chat** tab is the odd one out within Desktop — it is the claude.ai chat experience bolted into the same window, with no repo access; it is not the coding agent and won't read your `CLAUDE.md`. **Codex** is the genuine other product, covered at the end of this stage and throughout the course as a deliberate second agent — not a synonym for Claude Code.\n\n## The shared config: what makes them one tool\n**Shared config** is the set of files Claude Code reads at session start — instructions, settings, MCP servers, hooks, and skills — that *every* Claude Code front-end resolves the same way. This is the literal mechanism behind \"one tool, many front-ends.\" When the docs say the CLI and the Code tab \"share configuration,\" they mean these files on disk.\n\nThere are five categories. You'll meet each in depth later in the course; here is the map so the words stop blurring.\n\n| Category | What it controls | Canonical location(s) |\n|----------|------------------|------------------------|\n| **Instructions** | Persistent natural-language guidance to the agent | `./CLAUDE.md` or `./.claude/CLAUDE.md` (project), `~/.claude/CLAUDE.md` (user), `.claude/rules/*.md` (path-scoped) |\n| **Settings** | Permissions, env vars, model, behavior toggles | `.claude/settings.json`, `.claude/settings.local.json`, `~/.claude/settings.json`, `managed-settings.json` (policy) |\n| **MCP servers** | External tools/data the agent can call | `.mcp.json` (project root), `~/.claude.json` (user/local) |\n| **Hooks** | Shell commands that fire at lifecycle events (deterministic enforcement) | `.claude/settings.json` or a plugin's `hooks/hooks.json` |\n| **Skills** | On-demand procedures invokable as `/name` | `.claude/skills/<name>/SKILL.md`, `~/.claude/skills/...`, plugins |\n\n### The recurring two-axis pattern\n\nNearly every config type follows the same **scope × shared-ness** layout, which is worth internalizing now because it repeats:\n\n- **Project scope** lives in `.claude/` *in the repo* and is committed — this is your **team** config.\n- **User scope** lives in `~/.claude/` — personal, applies across all your projects.\n- **Local scope** is `*.local.*` in the repo, gitignored — personal overrides for *this* project. (MCP is the one exception: its \"local\" scope lives in `~/.claude.json`, not in the repo — covered in the MCP section.)\n- **Managed/policy** scope is IT-deployed and cannot be overridden by individuals.\n\nGet this layout in your head and every config file in the course slots into a known grid: *who does it apply to* (this project / all my projects / everyone in the org) and *is it committed* (team-shared / personal).\n\n## Instructions: CLAUDE.md (the team's shared brain)\n`CLAUDE.md` is the file you'll author first and touch most. It's plain markdown, loaded into context in full at the start of *every* session, on *every* front-end. Treat it as the thing you'd otherwise re-explain to a new teammate: build commands, conventions, architecture, \"always do X\" rules.\n\n### Locations and load order\n\nThe docs list them broadest-to-most-specific; later (more specific) files appear later in context. (Source: https://code.claude.com/docs/en/memory)\n\n| Scope | Location | Shared with |\n|-------|----------|-------------|\n| Managed policy | `/etc/claude-code/CLAUDE.md` (Linux/WSL), `/Library/Application Support/ClaudeCode/CLAUDE.md` (macOS), `C:\\Program Files\\ClaudeCode\\CLAUDE.md` (Windows) | All users in org (cannot be excluded) |\n| User | `~/.claude/CLAUDE.md` | Just you, all projects |\n| Project | `./CLAUDE.md` or `./.claude/CLAUDE.md` | **Team, via source control** |\n| Local | `./CLAUDE.local.md` (gitignore it) | Just you, this project |\n\nClaude walks *up* the directory tree from your cwd and concatenates every `CLAUDE.md` (and `CLAUDE.local.md`) it finds, ordered filesystem-root-down so instructions closest to where you launched are read last. Nested `CLAUDE.md` files in subdirectories load *on demand* when Claude reads files there — useful in monorepos.\n\n### Generating and importing\n\nRun `/init` to have Claude analyze the repo and draft a starting `CLAUDE.md` (if one exists, it suggests improvements rather than overwriting). You can also pull in other files with `@`-imports — resolved relative to the importing file, recursive to a max depth of four hops, and still loaded in full into context at launch:\n\n```markdown\n@AGENTS.md\n\n## Claude Code\nUse plan mode for changes under `src/billing/`.\n```\n\nThat `@AGENTS.md` import is the canonical bridge to Codex: the docs state *\"Claude Code reads `CLAUDE.md`, not `AGENTS.md`\"*, so importing it lets both agents share one instruction source. (Source: https://code.claude.com/docs/en/memory)\n\n### Gotchas\n\n- **It's context, not enforcement.** The docs are explicit: CLAUDE.md is *\"delivered as a user message after the system prompt\"* and *\"there's no guarantee of strict compliance.\"* To *block* an action regardless of what the model decides, use a **PreToolUse hook** or `permissions.deny`, not a CLAUDE.md sentence.\n- **Keep it under ~200 lines.** The docs recommend targeting under 200 lines; longer files consume more context and *reduce* adherence. Move procedures to skills and path-specific guidance to `.claude/rules/` (which can be scoped to globs via `paths:` frontmatter so they only load for matching files).\n- **Conflicts are silent.** If two CLAUDE.md files contradict, *\"Claude may pick one arbitrarily.\"* Audit periodically; in monorepos use the `claudeMdExcludes` setting to skip other teams' files.\n- **Don't confuse it with auto memory.** Claude also keeps a separate machine-local auto-memory at `~/.claude/projects/<project>/memory/MEMORY.md` that *Claude* writes; `CLAUDE.md` is the file *you* write and commit. Only `CLAUDE.md` is team-shared via git.\n\n## Settings & permissions: settings.json\n`settings.json` is the JSON config for behavior — most importantly **permissions**, which decide what the agent may do without asking. Same scope grid as CLAUDE.md, with a precise precedence.\n\n### Locations and precedence (highest wins)\n\n```\n1. Managed policy   (managed-settings.json — cannot be overridden)\n2. Command-line args\n3. .claude/settings.local.json   (local — personal, gitignored)\n4. .claude/settings.json         (project — committed, TEAM config)\n5. ~/.claude/settings.json        (user — all projects)\n```\n\nThe managed policy file is literally named `managed-settings.json` and lives in the OS policy directory: `/etc/claude-code/` (Linux/WSL), `/Library/Application Support/ClaudeCode/` (macOS), `C:\\Program Files\\ClaudeCode\\` (Windows). (Source: https://code.claude.com/docs/en/settings)\n\n### Example\n\n```json\n{\n  \"$schema\": \"https://json.schemastore.org/claude-code-settings.json\",\n  \"permissions\": {\n    \"allow\": [\n      \"Bash(npm run lint)\",\n      \"Bash(npm run test:*)\",\n      \"Read(~/.zshrc)\"\n    ],\n    \"ask\": [\n      \"Bash(git push:*)\"\n    ],\n    \"deny\": [\n      \"Read(./.env)\",\n      \"Read(./.env.*)\",\n      \"Read(./secrets/**)\"\n    ]\n  },\n  \"env\": { \"CLAUDE_CODE_ENABLE_TELEMETRY\": \"1\" },\n  \"model\": \"claude-sonnet-4-6\"\n}\n```\n\n### Permission rule syntax\n\nRules are `Tool(pattern)`. `Bash(npm run test:*)` matches a command prefix; `Read`/`Write` take glob paths (`*` = one segment, `**` = recursive). The three lists are `allow` (run silently), `ask` (prompt), `deny` (block). **Permission rules behave differently from other settings: they *merge* across scopes rather than override, and deny wins on conflict.** So a managed `deny` can't be unlocked by a project `allow`. (For technical enforcement the docs steer you to managed settings — `permissions.deny`, `sandbox.enabled`, `env` — and reserve CLAUDE.md for behavioral guidance.)\n\n### Why this is the heart of a team setup\n\nPermissions are the difference between \"the agent is a productivity tool\" and \"the agent `rm -rf`'d something at 2am.\" Because the project `settings.json` is committed, you author the team's safety envelope *once* and every front-end — terminal, Code tab, Cowork — enforces it identically. Personal experiments go in the gitignored `settings.local.json` so nobody has to touch the shared file to try something. (Source: https://code.claude.com/docs/en/settings)\n\n## External tools: .mcp.json\nMCP (Model Context Protocol) is how Claude Code talks to tools and data outside itself — a GitHub server, a database, an internal API, the codebase knowledge graph this very project"}, {"id": "stage-1", "title": "The Surfaces", "concepts": ["the CLI", "the Desktop Code tab", "headless mode", "Cowork", "Codex"], "claims": ["Claude Code's terminal CLI and the Desktop app 'Code' tab are the same engine reading the same config (CLAUDE.md, MCP, hooks, skills, settings).", "The Desktop 'Code' tab is distinct from the legacy Claude desktop chat app, whose MCP config (claude_desktop_config.json) is separate and does not appear in the Code tab.", "Headless / non-interactive mode (-p/--print, scripting, CI) is a terminal-CLI capability; the Desktop GUI is interactive only.", "Claude Cowork is agentic non-coding knowledge work that shows its plan before acting; available on paid plans including Team and Enterprise.", "Computer use and phone Dispatch are a Pro/Max research preview (macOS and Windows); the docs do NOT document Team/Enterprise exclusion, so 'not on Team' is an inference, restated as 'not part of the documented Team plan'.", "OpenAI Codex is a separate coding agent with its own config tree (~/.codex); nothing syncs automatically between Codex and Claude Code.", "Codex reads AGENTS.md for project instructions; Claude Code natively reads CLAUDE.md, NOT AGENTS.md, so teams bridge the two (symlink or generated mirror).", "Claude Code vs Codex is not either/or; the productive pattern is to run both."], "content": "## The question behind the question\nWhen you stand up shared agentic-coding infrastructure, the first thing your team will ask is deceptively simple: *\"Which one do I open?\"* They mean: terminal, desktop app, the thing my non-engineer PM is using, the OpenAI tool half the team prefers. The wrong answer wastes weeks. A backend dev who only knows the GUI will hand-edit JSON that should have been a `claude -p` one-liner in CI. An ops teammate who never hears about Cowork will keep doing by hand the cross-app drudgery that surface was built to absorb. A reviewer who assumes Codex and Claude Code share config will wonder why their carefully written `CLAUDE.md` is invisible to half the team.\n\nThe honest answer is **not one tool — it's a menu**, and most items on the menu are the *same capability projected onto a different surface*, with one critical exception (Codex, which is a different vendor entirely). This stage maps the menu precisely: what each surface is, what it can and cannot do, where its config lives, and the failure modes you hit when you pick wrong.\n\n### The mental model: one engine, several surfaces, one foreign agent\n\nThree of the five things on this menu — the terminal CLI, the Desktop **Code** tab, and headless mode — are the *same Claude Code engine*. The official desktop docs say it plainly: \"Desktop runs the same engine as the CLI with a graphical interface... they share configuration (CLAUDE.md files, MCP servers, hooks, skills, and settings)\" ([desktop quickstart](https://code.claude.com/docs/en/desktop-quickstart)). Cowork is a fourth surface of Anthropic's agentic capability aimed at non-developers. Codex is a *separate product from OpenAI* with its own engine and its own config tree. Hold that shape in your head: **don't reason about \"Claude Code the GUI vs Claude Code the CLI\" as two products** — they are one product reading one config, shown two ways.\n\n## Surface 1 — the CLI (the terminal): the scriptable core\nThe CLI is `claude` in your terminal. It is the canonical, lowest-level surface: everything the other Claude Code surfaces do, this can do, plus the things *only* a terminal can do (pipe stdin, redirect stdout, exit codes, run inside CI with no display).\n\n### What it is\n\nAn interactive REPL when you run `claude` bare, and a one-shot tool when you add `-p`. It reads the full configuration stack at startup: `CLAUDE.md` files up the directory tree, `~/.claude/` user config, MCP servers from `.mcp.json`, hooks, skills, and `settings.json`.\n\n### Why a team standardizes on it as the base layer\n\n- **Scriptable and automatable.** It composes with the rest of your shell. A `package.json` script can call it; a Makefile target can call it; a git hook can call it.\n- **Reproducible.** With the right flags (see headless, below) you get identical behavior across machines.\n- **Universal.** It is the only surface available on Linux — the docs state \"The desktop app is not available on Linux; use the CLI instead\" ([desktop quickstart](https://code.claude.com/docs/en/desktop-quickstart)). Your CI runners and remote boxes are almost always Linux, so the CLI is the only surface that runs *everywhere your code runs*.\n\n### Concrete: starting an interactive session\n\n```bash\ncd ~/projects/godel\nclaude                          # interactive REPL in this repo\nclaude --model claude-opus-4-8  # pin a model\nclaude --add-dir ../shared-lib  # grant access to a sibling dir\n```\n\nInside the REPL, `/memory` lists which `CLAUDE.md`, `CLAUDE.local.md`, and rules files loaded (and toggles auto memory), `/config` changes settings, and `/skill-name` invokes a skill. The point of the CLI is that *all* of these are also reachable non-interactively — which is the next surface.\n\n### One menu, one table\n\n| Surface | Engine | OS | Headless? | Config read |\n|---|---|---|---|---|\n| CLI (`claude`) | Claude Code | macOS / Windows / **Linux** | yes (`-p`) | full Claude Code stack |\n| Headless (`claude -p`) | Claude Code | same as CLI | yes (it *is* the mode) | full stack, or none with `--bare` |\n| Desktop **Code** tab | Claude Code | macOS / Windows only | no (interactive) | same stack as CLI |\n| Cowork | Anthropic agent (cloud VM) | macOS / Windows desktop | n/a (autonomous) | connectors, not CLAUDE.md |\n| Codex | **OpenAI** | macOS / Windows / Linux | yes (`codex exec`) | `~/.codex` (TOML) |\n\n## Surface 2 — headless mode: the same engine, no human in the loop\nHeadless mode is not a separate program. It is the CLI run **non-interactively** with `-p` (alias `--print`): one prompt in, output out, then exit. This is what you put in scripts, git hooks, and CI. Per the docs, this non-interactive mode is a **terminal-CLI capability — the Desktop GUI is interactive only** ([headless docs](https://code.claude.com/docs/en/headless)).\n\n### The shape of a headless call\n\n```bash\nclaude -p \"What does the auth module do?\"\n```\n\nIt reads stdin, so it composes like any Unix filter:\n\n```bash\ncat build-error.txt | claude -p 'concisely explain the root cause of this build error' > output.txt\n```\n\nAs of Claude Code v2.1.128, piped stdin is capped at 10MB; beyond that, Claude Code exits with a clear error and a non-zero status, so write to a file and reference the path in the prompt instead.\n\n### Structured output for scripts\n\n`--output-format` controls the response shape — `text` (default), `json` (result + session id + cost metadata), or `stream-json` (newline-delimited events for live streaming). For schema-constrained output, combine `--output-format json` with `--json-schema`; the structured payload lands in the `structured_output` field:\n\n```bash\nclaude -p \"Extract the main function names from auth.py\" \\\n  --output-format json \\\n  --json-schema '{\"type\":\"object\",\"properties\":{\"functions\":{\"type\":\"array\",\"items\":{\"type\":\"string\"}}},\"required\":[\"functions\"]}' \\\n  | jq '.structured_output'\n```\n\nThe `json` payload includes `total_cost_usd` and a per-model cost breakdown, so a scripted caller can track spend per invocation without opening a dashboard. For live streaming, pair `--output-format stream-json` with `--verbose --include-partial-messages` and filter `text_delta` events with `jq`.\n\n### Auto-approving tools (the part everyone gets wrong first)\n\nIn an interactive session you approve each tool use. In headless mode there is no human to approve, so an un-pre-approved tool **aborts the run**. You grant permission up front:\n\n```bash\nclaude -p \"Run the test suite and fix any failures\" \\\n  --allowedTools \"Bash,Read,Edit\"\n```\n\n`--allowedTools` uses [permission-rule syntax](https://code.claude.com/docs/en/settings#permission-rule-syntax), so you can scope Bash narrowly. The trailing space-then-`*` is load-bearing:\n\n```bash\nclaude -p \"Look at my staged changes and create an appropriate commit\" \\\n  --allowedTools \"Bash(git diff *),Bash(git log *),Bash(git status *),Bash(git commit *)\"\n```\n\nThe docs are explicit: `Bash(git diff *)` allows any command starting with `git diff`, and \"the space before `*` is important: without it, `Bash(git diff*)` would also match `git diff-index`.\" For a whole-session baseline instead of listing tools, pass a [permission mode](https://code.claude.com/docs/en/permission-modes): `--permission-mode acceptEdits` (auto-writes files and auto-approves common fs commands like `mkdir`, `touch`, `mv`, `cp` — other shell/network calls still need an `--allowedTools` entry) or `--permission-mode dontAsk` (denies anything not in `permissions.allow` or the read-only command set — the locked-down CI choice).\n\n### `--bare`: reproducibility for CI\n\n`claude --bare -p ...` skips auto-discovery of hooks, skills, plugins, MCP servers, auto memory, and `CLAUDE.md`. The docs call this \"the recommended mode for scripted and SDK calls\" and say it \"will become the default for `-p` in a future release.\" The motivation is sharp: *a hook in a teammate's `~/.claude` or an MCP server in the repo's `.mcp.json` won't silently change your CI result, because bare mode never reads them.* In bare mode Claude still has Bash, file-read, and file-edit tools; you pass everything else explicitly:\n\n```bash\nclaude --bare -p \"Summarize this file\" --allowedTools \"Read\" \\\n  --settings ./ci-settings.json \\\n  --mcp-config ./ci-mcp.json\n```\n\nNote bare mode skips OAuth/keychain reads — Anthropic auth must come from `ANTHROPIC_API_KEY` or an `apiKeyHelper` in the JSON passed to `--settings` (Bedrock/Vertex/Foundry use their usual provider credentials).\n\n### Use it as a project linter / reviewer\n\n```json\n{\n  \"scripts\": {\n    \"lint:claude\": \"git diff main | claude -p \\\"you are a typo linter. for each typo in this diff, report filename:line on one line and the issue on the next. return nothing else.\\\"\"\n  }\n}\n```\n\nPiping the diff means Claude doesn't even need Bash permission to read it. Add `--bare` for CI so the runner's ambient config can't change the result.\n\n## Surface 3 — the Desktop Code tab: the same engine with a GUI\nThe Desktop app's **Code** tab is Claude Code with a graphical interface. The single most important fact to drill into your team, straight from the docs: \"Desktop runs the same engine as the CLI with a graphical interface. You can run both simultaneously on the same project, and they share configuration (CLAUDE.md files, MCP servers, hooks, skills, and settings)\" ([desktop quickstart](https://code.claude.com/docs/en/desktop-quickstart)). They do not have divergent behavior. Note the app is macOS/Windows only (universal macOS build; Windows x64 and ARM64) — there is no Linux desktop, and Claude Code requires a Pro, Max, Team, or Enterprise subscription.\n\n### What the GUI adds over the terminal\n\nThe Desktop app is described as \"built for running multiple sessions side by side\" with a visual review loop:\n\n- **Visual diff review.** Claude proposes a change; you see a file-by-file diff with Accept/Reject buttons and can comment on specific lines, which Claude reads and revises. Clicking **Review code** has Claude evaluate its own diffs and leave inline suggestions.\n- **Drag-and-drop panes.** Chat, diff, integrated terminal (open with **Ctrl+`**), file editor, and live app **Preview** (run your dev server inside the app; Claude can view the running app, test endpoints, and inspect logs).\n- **Parallel sessions, each in its own git worktree.** This is the headline capability: open multiple sessions from the sidebar, \"each in its own Git worktree,\" so concurrent tasks don't stomp on each other's working tree. A tasks pane shows the subagents and background commands a session is running; a *side chat* lets you ask a question without derailing the main thread.\n- **PR monitoring + auto-merge, scheduled tasks, remote/SSH environments.** It monitors CI check results and \"can automatically fix failures or merge the PR once all checks pass\"; it runs scheduled tasks (daily review, weekly dep audit, briefings); and sessions run **Local**, **Remote** (Anthropic cloud — \"continue even if you close the app\"), or over **SSH** (it installs Claude Code on the remote machine the first time you connect).\n\n### The permission modes mirror the CLI\n\n| Desktop mode | CLI equivalent | Behavior |\n|---|---|---|\n| Ask permissions (default) | (interactive default) | Approve before every edit |\n| Auto accept edits | `--permission-mode acceptEdits` | Auto-applies file edits |\n| Plan mode | `--permission-mode plan` | Maps an approach, touches no files |\n\n### The gotcha that costs teams a day: Code tab ≠ legacy Claude desktop chat app\n\nThe desktop app has three tabs — **Chat** (\"general conversation with no file access, similar to claude.ai\"), **Cowork** (\"an autonomous background agent that works on tasks in a cloud VM,\" covered below), and **Code**. The **Code** tab is distinct from the *legacy Claude desktop chat app*, whose MCP configuration lives in a separate `claude_desktop_config.json` that **does not appear in the Code tab** ([desktop quickstart](https://code.claude.com/docs/en/desktop-quickstart), [issue #33732](https://github.com/anthropics/claude-code/issues/33732)). So if a teammate added an MCP server to the old chat app's `claude_desktop_config.json` and wonders why the Code tab can't see it — that's why. Code-tab MCP comes from Claude Code's own config (`.mcp.json`, user/project settings, or the Code tab's **+ → Plugins** UI), the *same* config the CLI reads, not from `claude_desktop_config.json`.\n\n## Surface 4 — Cowork: the same agentic capability for non-developers\nCowork is the same agentic loop — give it a goal, it plans, it acts across your stuff — pointed at **non-coding knowledge work**. It is the surface you point your PMs, ops, analysts, and support leads at. The docs describe the Cowork tab as \"an autonomous background agent that works on tasks in a cloud VM with its own environment\" that \"can run independently while you do other work\"; the product page frames it as agentic non-coding knowledge work that shows its plan before acting, available on paid plans including Team and Enterprise ([Cowork product page](https://claude.com/product/cowork), [support article](https://support.claude.com/en/articles/13345190)).\n\n### What it does\n\nHand off a task, get a polished deliverable: organizing file systems, building spreadsheets, generating reports, synthesizing scattered notes, scheduling recurring tasks. The defining property for trust: **before Claude acts, it shows you the plan and waits for your approval** — you can redirect, refine, or change approach at any step. This is the difference between \"an agent that ran amok in my Drive\" and \"an agent I supervised.\"\n\n### How it reaches your tools\n\nCowork works across apps using a **connector for Slack, Chrome for web research, or your screen** to drive apps that have no direct integration. You keep access controls over which folders and connectors it may use. It is one of the three desktop tabs and, because it runs as an autonomous background agent in a cloud VM, it continues while you do other work; mobile can initiate tasks via phone pairing.\n\n### Why "}, {"id": "stage-2", "title": "Config as Code", "concepts": ["CLAUDE.md", "AGENTS.md", "the config mirror", "the .claude directory", "settings.json"], "claims": ["A committed .claude/ directory travels with the repo: cloning it (and accepting the trust dialog) gives a teammate the project skills, agents, hooks, and settings.json.", "Codex reads AGENTS.md for project instructions; Claude Code natively reads CLAUDE.md, NOT AGENTS.md, so teams bridge the two (symlink or generated mirror).", "AGENTS.md is an open standard stewarded by the Agentic AI Foundation (Linux Foundation), used by ~60k projects and 20+ tools.", "The dominant CLAUDE.md anti-pattern at scale is the over-stuffed, unowned file; keep it short (~<200 lines), give it an owner, review it like code, and use a root + per-package Context Cascade.", "To make 'configure once' span Claude Code and Codex, keep one canonical config and project it: generate-or-symlink AGENTS.md from CLAUDE.md, and mirror skills into each tool's dir (a portable source like ~/.agents/skills symlinked into .claude/skills and Codex's surface), with a drift check that fails CI on divergence. This lets a dev switch between the two tools in VS Code and get identical rules.", "Claude Code settings (permissions, hooks, env) live in .claude/settings.json (committed for the team) with personal overrides in .claude/settings.local.json; settings merge across scopes with the higher scope winning per key.", "Claude Code access control is allow/ask/deny permission rules — tool-name glob patterns (e.g. Bash(git push:*), Read(./.env.*), mcp__*) in settings.json permissions{}. Rules evaluate deny → ask → allow, first-match-wins; the allow/ask/deny arrays MERGE (concatenate) across scopes, so a higher-scope (managed or user) deny is a floor no lower scope can relax.", "Claude Code reads ONLY CLAUDE.md, not AGENTS.md (not even as a fallback). The cross-platform single-source bridge is a first-line `@AGENTS.md` import in CLAUDE.md (recursive up to 4 hops; works on Windows without admin), preferred over an `ln -s AGENTS.md CLAUDE.md` symlink (Windows needs core.symlinks + admin/Developer Mode)."], "content": "## The bug isn't in the prompt — it's in the room\nTwo engineers paste the same prompt — \"add input validation to the billing endpoint\" — into the same repo. One gets code with Pydantic models, structured logging, and a test. The other gets a bare `if not x: return`. Same model, same prompt, same files. The difference is everything the agent loaded *before* the prompt: one teammate has a `CLAUDE.md` that says \"API handlers validate with Pydantic and log all state changes,\" a `.claude/settings.json` that denies `Bash(git push:*)` so the agent doesn't surprise-push, and a skill that knows the house test command. The other teammate is running bare.\n\nThis is the central insight of this stage: **an agent's behavior is a function of its configuration, and configuration is usually invisible.** Nobody reviews it, nobody versions it, nobody diffs it. When the prompt is the only artifact you share, you're sharing the smallest, least important part of the setup. The fix is to treat the *setup itself* — instructions, permissions, hooks, skills — as code: one canonical source, committed, reviewed in PRs, and projected to every engine your team uses (Claude Code and Codex) so switching tools doesn't mean re-teaching each one.\n\nThe rest of this stage is the concrete machinery: what `CLAUDE.md` and `AGENTS.md` are and how to keep them from diverging, what lives in `.claude/`, how `settings.json` permissions and precedence actually evaluate, and the failure modes that bite teams at scale. Throughout, keep one line from the official docs in mind, because it draws the sharpest boundary in the whole stage: \"Settings rules are enforced by the client regardless of what Claude decides to do. CLAUDE.md instructions shape Claude's behavior but are not a hard enforcement layer.\"\n\n## CLAUDE.md: the always-loaded instruction file\n`CLAUDE.md` is a plain-markdown file Claude Code loads into context at the **start of every session**. It is not a system prompt and not enforced configuration — the docs are explicit: \"CLAUDE.md content is delivered as a user message after the system prompt, not as part of the system prompt itself. Claude reads it and tries to follow it, but there's no guarantee of strict compliance.\" It *shapes* what the agent tries to do; it does not *guarantee* anything. (For hard guarantees you need hooks and permission rules — covered below.)\n\n### What goes in it\nThe load-bearing content is the stuff you'd otherwise re-explain every session. The docs frame the trigger as: add to `CLAUDE.md` when \"Claude makes the same mistake a second time,\" \"a code review catches something Claude should have known,\" or \"a new teammate would need the same context.\"\n- Build/test commands (`npm run check`, `make test`)\n- Project layout (\"API handlers live in `src/api/handlers/`\")\n- Conventions and \"always do X\" rules\n- Architecture decisions and gotchas a new teammate would need\n\nIf an entry is a multi-step *procedure* or only matters for one part of the tree, the docs say to move it to a skill or a path-scoped rule instead — not to grow `CLAUDE.md`.\n\n### Where it can live (load order, broad → specific)\n| Scope | Location | Shared with |\n|---|---|---|\n| Managed policy | `/Library/Application Support/ClaudeCode/CLAUDE.md` (macOS), `/etc/claude-code/CLAUDE.md` (Linux/WSL), `C:\\Program Files\\ClaudeCode\\CLAUDE.md` (Windows) | All users on machine (IT-deployed; cannot be excluded) |\n| User | `~/.claude/CLAUDE.md` | Just you, every project |\n| Project | `./CLAUDE.md` or `./.claude/CLAUDE.md` | The team, via git |\n| Local | `./CLAUDE.local.md` (gitignore it) | Just you, this repo |\n\nClaude walks **up** the directory tree from your cwd and concatenates every `CLAUDE.md` and `CLAUDE.local.md` it finds. Content is ordered root-first (\"from the filesystem root down to your working directory\"), so instructions closest to where you launched are read **last**; within a directory, `CLAUDE.local.md` is appended after `CLAUDE.md`. Subdirectory `CLAUDE.md` files load **on demand** when Claude reads files there — this is the \"context cascade\" that makes per-package instructions work without bloating every session.\n\n### Specificity is the whole game\nThe docs measure adherence by specificity. \"Use 2-space indentation\" beats \"Format code properly\"; \"Run `npm test` before committing\" beats \"Test your changes\"; \"API handlers live in `src/api/handlers/`\" beats \"Keep files organized.\" Write instructions concrete enough to *verify*. Vague rules and — worse — *contradictory* rules across nested files cause Claude to \"pick one arbitrarily.\"\n\n## Keep CLAUDE.md short, owned, and reviewed\nThe dominant anti-pattern at scale is the **over-stuffed, unowned `CLAUDE.md`** — a 600-line file nobody owns, everyone appends to, and that quietly contradicts itself. Two reasons this is corrosive:\n\n1. **Context cost.** `CLAUDE.md` loads *in full* every session regardless of length (the docs: \"CLAUDE.md files are loaded in full regardless of length, though shorter files produce better adherence\"). The docs set an explicit target: **target under 200 lines per file**. Longer files \"consume more context and reduce adherence\" — the irony being that the more you cram in to control the agent, the *less* reliably it follows any of it.\n2. **Rot.** An unowned file accumulates stale rules. When two rules conflict, behavior becomes nondeterministic — \"Claude may pick one arbitrarily.\"\n\n### The three disciplines\n- **Give it an owner.** Someone is responsible for pruning. The test from the docs: add a line when \"Claude makes the same mistake a second time\" or \"a new teammate would need the same context\" — not speculatively.\n- **Review it like code.** Changes to `CLAUDE.md` go through PR review. A new \"always do X\" rule is a behavioral change to every agent session on the team; it deserves the same scrutiny as a code change.\n- **Cascade instead of cramming.** Use a root `CLAUDE.md` for project-wide facts and **`.claude/rules/`** (or per-package files) for the local stuff. Rules go in `.claude/rules/<topic>.md`; a rule *without* a `paths:` frontmatter loads every session (same priority as `.claude/CLAUDE.md`), while a **path-scoped** rule loads only when Claude touches matching files:\n\n```markdown\n---\npaths:\n  - \"src/api/**/*.ts\"\n---\n# API rules\n- All API endpoints must include input validation\n- Use the standard error response format\n```\n\nA path-scoped rule costs zero context until the agent opens a matching file. That's how you keep the always-loaded surface small while still encoding deep, local knowledge. (`paths` accepts glob patterns and brace expansion: `\"src/**/*.{ts,tsx}\"`.)\n\n### Imports for organization\n`CLAUDE.md` can pull in other files with `@path/to/file` syntax. Relative paths resolve against the *importing* file (not cwd); imports recurse to a **maximum depth of four hops**. Caveat from the docs: imported files \"are expanded and loaded into context at launch,\" so imports buy *organization*, not context savings — \"Splitting into `@path` imports helps organization but does not reduce context.\" To mention a path without importing it, wrap it in backticks (`` `@README` ``). The first time a project uses external imports, Claude shows a one-time approval dialog listing the files.\n\n### One thing the docs preserve\nBlock-level HTML comments (`<!-- maintainer notes -->`) are stripped before injection, so you can leave human-only notes that cost zero context. Project-root `CLAUDE.md` is also re-read and re-injected after `/compact` — nested subdirectory files are not, so anything that must survive compaction belongs at the root (or in a hook).\n\n## AGENTS.md: the Codex-facing mirror\n`AGENTS.md` is the same idea — a markdown file giving AI coding agents project context — but it's the **open standard** the rest of the ecosystem reads. Per agents.md it is \"stewarded by the Agentic AI Foundation under the Linux Foundation,\" \"used by over 60k open-source projects,\" and read by **25+ tools** including OpenAI Codex, Google Jules, Aider, goose, Cursor, Gemini CLI, VS Code, Devin, and GitHub Copilot's coding agent. The format is deliberately minimal: \"AGENTS.md is just standard Markdown. Use any headings you like; the agent simply parses the text you provide.\" There are no required fields.\n\nFor monorepos, AGENTS.md uses **closest-file-wins**: \"The closest AGENTS.md to the edited file wins; explicit user chat prompts override everything.\" Each subproject ships tailored instructions — the same cascade idea as nested `CLAUDE.md`.\n\n### How Codex actually reads it\nCodex's discovery is concrete and worth knowing, because it shapes how you place files. Per the Codex docs, Codex reads, in order, from your Codex home (`~/.codex` unless `CODEX_HOME` is set) then from the project root down to cwd, checking each directory for `AGENTS.override.md`, then `AGENTS.md`, then fallback names. It \"concatenates files from the root down, joining them with blank lines,\" and \"files closer to your current directory override earlier guidance because they appear later in the combined prompt.\" Instructions are capped at `project_doc_max_bytes` (**32 KiB by default**) before truncation.\n\n### The asymmetry that creates the whole problem\nHere is the fact that drives this stage's design, and it's easy to get wrong:\n\n> **Claude Code reads ONLY `CLAUDE.md`. It does not read `AGENTS.md` — not even as a fallback.** The docs say it directly: \"Claude Code reads `CLAUDE.md`, not `AGENTS.md`.\"\n\nCodex reads `AGENTS.md`. Claude reads `CLAUDE.md`. They do not natively share a file. So a team that uses both engines — or even a single dev who switches between Claude Code and Codex in VS Code — has two instruction files that *will* drift unless you do something about it. (Note: the agents.md tool list does **not** include Claude Code; trust Claude's own docs here — the native reader is `CLAUDE.md`, and the bridge below is how Claude participates in the standard.)\n\nThat \"something\" is the config mirror.\n\n## The config mirror: one canonical source, projected\nThe principle: **keep ONE canonical config and project it to the other engine** rather than hand-maintaining two files that silently fall out of sync. There are two mechanically different ways to bridge `CLAUDE.md` ↔ `AGENTS.md`, and the choice matters for cross-platform teams.\n\n### Option A — the `@AGENTS.md` import (preferred, portable)\nMake `AGENTS.md` the canonical file (it's the open standard, the broader-reach format) and have `CLAUDE.md` import it. This is the exact pattern the Claude docs recommend:\n\n```markdown CLAUDE.md\n@AGENTS.md\n\n## Claude Code\nUse plan mode for changes under `src/billing/`.\n```\n\nClaude \"loads the imported file at session start, then appends the rest.\" This works on **Windows with no admin rights**, recurses up to four hops, and lets you add engine-specific notes below the import. This is the recommended bridge.\n\n### Option B — the symlink\nIf you don't need Claude-specific content, symlink the two — also shown in the Claude docs:\n\n```bash\nln -s AGENTS.md CLAUDE.md\n```\n\nNow both engines read the same bytes. The catch, stated in the docs: \"On Windows, creating a symlink requires Administrator privileges or Developer Mode, so use the `@AGENTS.md` import instead.\" (Mixed-OS teams hit a second snag: git only materializes the symlink as a real link when `core.symlinks` is enabled on the Windows clone; otherwise it checks out as a plain text file containing the path string.) Use the symlink only on all-POSIX teams.\n\n### Comparison\n| | `@AGENTS.md` import | `ln -s AGENTS.md CLAUDE.md` symlink |\n|---|---|---|\n| Canonical file | `AGENTS.md` | `AGENTS.md` |\n| Windows without admin | Works | Needs Admin / Developer Mode |\n| Add Claude-only content | Yes, below the import | No (identical bytes) |\n| Recursion / nesting | Up to 4 hops | N/A |\n| Risk of silent drift | Low (single source) | None (literally one file) |\n\n### The generated-projection variant\nA third pattern, used in this very ecosystem, treats `CLAUDE.md` (or a `relationships.yaml`) as canonical and **deterministically renders** `AGENTS.md` from it — see `project-meta/scripts/meta/render_agents_md.py`, which extracts a fixed set of sections \"without making `AGENTS.md` a second hand-maintained authority.\" Use this when the two files need different *shapes* (e.g., Codex wants a flattened projection, or you want only some sections mirrored), not just different bytes. Whatever you pick, the rule is the same: **exactly one file is authored by hand; the other is derived.**\n\n## The drift check: fail CI when the mirror diverges\nA mirror is only as good as the thing that catches it breaking. The discipline that makes \"configure once\" real is a **drift check in CI** that fails the build when the canonical source and its projection diverge. Without it, the import or symlink is a *convention*, and conventions rot.\n\nThis ecosystem ships exactly such a check: `project-meta/scripts/check_agent_surface_sync.py`. It is \"intentionally read-only\" and \"reports whether the workspace root instruction files resolve to the same content and whether Claude/Codex skill discovery directories have obvious mirror drift.\" The mechanism is a content hash: render the projection, hash it, compare to the committed file.\n\n### What a drift gate looks like in CI\n```yaml\n# .github/workflows/agent-config.yml\nname: agent-config\non: [push, pull_request]\njobs:\n  surface-sync:\n    runs-on: ubuntu-latest\n    steps:\n      - uses: actions/checkout@v4\n      - uses: actions/setup-python@v5\n        with: { python-version: \"3.12\" }\n      - name: Re-render AGENTS.md and fail on diff\n        run: python scripts/meta/render_agents_md.py --check\n      - name: Hash CLAUDE.md vs AGENTS.md + skill dirs\n        run: python scripts/check_agent_surface_sync.py\n```\n\nThe `--check` mode re-renders the projection and exits non-zero if it differs from what's committed — the same pattern as `black --check` or `prettier --check`. A reviewer who edits `AGENTS.md` but forgets to regenerate (or edits the wrong fil"}, {"id": "stage-3", "title": "Capabilities", "concepts": ["a skill", "progressive disclosure", "a sub-agent", "a hook", "an MCP server", "a portable skill"], "claims": ["Agent Skills use the open SKILL.md format supported by both Claude Code and Codex, but each tool reads only its OWN skills directory (Claude .claude/skills, Codex .agents/skills); portability = author once, mirror into each tool's dir.", "Skills are model-invoked via their description (progressive disclosure: discovery loads name+description, activation loads SKILL.md, bundled references load only when accessed).", "Hooks fire deterministically on event+matcher conditions, independent of the model's choice, and can hard-block (exit 2 / deny); handlers can be shell commands, HTTP endpoints, MCP tool calls, LLM prompts, or subagents, across many events beyond PreToolUse/PostToolUse.", "Each subagent runs in its own context window with a custom system prompt, restricted (least-privilege) tool access, and returns only a summary to the main context.", "For supplying always-true knowledge, a static docs-index (AGENTS.md/CLAUDE.md) currently outperforms model-invoked Skills in published evals.", "Loading many MCP tools consumes a large share of the context window before work begins; the open question is whether to restrict tools or compress outputs.", "To make 'configure once' span Claude Code and Codex, keep one canonical config and project it: generate-or-symlink AGENTS.md from CLAUDE.md, and mirror skills into each tool's dir (a portable source like ~/.agents/skills symlinked into .claude/skills and Codex's surface), with a drift check that fails CI on divergence. This lets a dev switch between the two tools in VS Code and get identical rules."], "content": "## The itch this stage scratches\nYou notice it the tenth time you paste the same five-step deploy checklist into chat. Or when a teammate force-pushes to `main` *again* despite the line in `CLAUDE.md` that says not to. Or when you realize half your context window is gone before you've typed a word, eaten by an MCP server you wired up last week and forgot about.\n\nThose are distinct itches, and they map to distinct mechanisms. Getting the mapping right is the whole game:\n\n- **\"I keep re-describing a *procedure*\"** → a **skill**. On-demand, model-invoked, loaded only when relevant.\n- **\"A rule must *always* hold, no matter what the model decides\"** → a **hook**. Deterministic, event-driven, can hard-block.\n- **\"I want a *bounded* sub-task done without polluting my main context\"** → a **sub-agent**. Own window, least-privilege tools, returns a summary.\n- **\"I need Claude to *reach into* an external system\"** → an **MCP server**. A typed gateway to GitHub, a database, a tracker.\n\nThe failure mode is reaching for the wrong one: encoding a non-negotiable policy as advisory `CLAUDE.md` prose (it gets ignored under load), or bolting a 40-tool MCP server onto every session when a CLI call would do. This stage goes deep on each primitive, its real file format, and the decision boundary between them. Everything below is the actual on-disk format as of mid-2026 — verified against `code.claude.com/docs`, `developers.openai.com/codex`, and `agentskills.io`, not from memory.\n\n## Skills: a capability whose description is its trigger\nA **skill** is an on-demand capability packaged as a directory with a `SKILL.md` entrypoint. The defining property: **it is model-invoked via its description.** At session start Claude loads only each skill's `name` + `description` (cheap). When your request matches a description, Claude loads the full `SKILL.md` body and follows it. You can also fire it explicitly with `/skill-name`.\n\nThe docs give a one-line decision rule (code.claude.com/docs/en/skills): create a skill *\"when you keep pasting the same instructions, checklist, or multi-step procedure into chat, or when a section of CLAUDE.md has grown into a procedure rather than a fact.\"* A fact belongs in `CLAUDE.md`; a *procedure* belongs in a skill, because the skill's body loads only when used, so long reference material costs almost nothing until you need it.\n\nNote: in Claude Code, **custom commands have been merged into skills.** A file at `.claude/commands/deploy.md` and a skill at `.claude/skills/deploy/SKILL.md` both create `/deploy`; the skill form just adds a directory for supporting files, frontmatter for invocation control, and automatic model invocation.\n\n### File layout\n\n```text\n.claude/skills/\n└── summarize-changes/\n    ├── SKILL.md          # required entrypoint\n    ├── reference.md      # optional, loaded only when referenced\n    └── scripts/\n        └── validate.sh    # optional, executed not loaded\n```\n\nThe **directory name** becomes the `/command` you type. The frontmatter `name` is only a display label shown in listings — *except* at a plugin root, where there is no skill directory and `name` does set the command.\n\n### SKILL.md frontmatter\n\nThe docs' canonical first example carries only a `description` — every other field is optional:\n\n```yaml\n---\ndescription: Summarizes uncommitted changes and flags anything risky. Use when the user asks what changed, wants a commit message, or asks to review their diff.\n---\n\n## Current changes\n\n!`git diff HEAD`\n\n## Instructions\n\nSummarize the changes above in two or three bullet points, then list any risks.\n```\n\nThe `` !`git diff HEAD` `` line is **dynamic context injection**: Claude Code runs the command *before* the model sees the body and inlines the output (this is preprocessing — Claude never executes it). For multi-line, use a ` ```! ` fenced block. The inline form only fires when `!` starts a line or follows whitespace; `KEY=!`cmd`` is left literal.\n\n## Skill frontmatter fields that actually matter\nEvery frontmatter field is optional; only `description` is *recommended* (without it Claude has nothing to match on, and falls back to the first paragraph of the body). Here are the fields you will actually reach for (code.claude.com/docs/en/skills, frontmatter reference):\n\n| Field | Effect |\n|-------|--------|\n| `description` | The trigger. Put the key use case first. Combined `description` + `when_to_use` is truncated at **1,536 chars** in the listing (configurable via `maxSkillDescriptionChars`). |\n| `when_to_use` | Extra trigger phrases / example requests, appended to `description`; counts toward the 1,536-char cap. |\n| `disable-model-invocation: true` | Only *you* can invoke (`/name`); description is not even loaded into context. Use for side-effecting workflows — `/deploy`, `/commit` — you don't want Claude auto-running. |\n| `user-invocable: false` | Hide from the `/` menu; only *Claude* invokes. Use for background knowledge that isn't a meaningful user command. |\n| `allowed-tools` | Pre-approve tools while the skill is active (e.g. `Bash(git add *) Bash(git commit *)`). Does **not** restrict the pool — it just skips the permission prompt. |\n| `disallowed-tools` | *Removes* tools from the pool while the skill is active (e.g. `AskUserQuestion` for a background loop). Clears on your next message. |\n| `context: fork` + `agent` | Run the skill in a sub-agent's isolated context (see the sub-agent section). |\n| `model` / `effort` | Override the model or effort level for the rest of the turn while the skill is active. |\n| `argument-hint` / `arguments` | Autocomplete hint and named `$arg` substitution. |\n| `paths` | Glob patterns; auto-activate the skill only when working on matching files. |\n\n### Arguments\n\nArguments arrive via `$ARGUMENTS` (full string), `$ARGUMENTS[0]` / shorthand `$0` (0-based positional), or named `$issue` when declared in `arguments:`. Indexed args use shell-style quoting — `/my-skill \"hello world\" second` makes `$0` = `hello world`. If you pass args but the body has no placeholder, Claude Code appends `ARGUMENTS: <value>` so the model still sees them. Other useful substitutions: `${CLAUDE_SKILL_DIR}` (resolves bundled-script paths regardless of cwd), `${CLAUDE_SESSION_ID}`, `${CLAUDE_EFFORT}`.\n\n### Pitfall: malformed frontmatter\n\nIf the YAML is malformed, Claude Code loads the body with **empty metadata** — `/name` still works, but there's no `description` to match, so model invocation silently never fires. Run `claude --debug` to surface the parse error.\n\n## Progressive disclosure: why a lean skill stays cheap\n**Progressive disclosure** is the mechanism that lets you have dozens of skills without drowning context. It works in three tiers (code.claude.com/docs/en/skills, docs.claude.com agent-skills overview):\n\n1. **Discovery** — only `name` + `description` are in context for every skill. This is what the model matches against.\n2. **Activation** — when a skill is selected, the full `SKILL.md` content enters the conversation as a single message and *stays for the rest of the session*. Claude Code does **not** re-read the file on later turns.\n3. **Bundled references** — files like `reference.md` load only when Claude actually opens them, because you pointed at them from `SKILL.md`.\n\n### The two design consequences\n\n**Keep the body lean.** Once activated, the body is a recurring per-turn token cost — it just sits in context. The docs cap the recommendation at **500 lines** for `SKILL.md` and tell you to push detail into separate files:\n\n```markdown\n## Additional resources\n- For the full API surface, see [reference.md](reference.md)\n- For worked examples, see [examples.md](examples.md)\n```\n\nClaude loads `reference.md` only if the task needs it. A 4,000-line API spec next to a 60-line `SKILL.md` costs nothing until the moment it's relevant. (One subtlety: after auto-compaction, Claude Code re-attaches only the most recent invocation of each skill, keeping the first 5,000 tokens, under a shared 25,000-token budget — so a huge body can be silently truncated post-compaction. Re-invoke to restore it.)\n\n**Mind the listing budget.** All skill *names* are always listed, but descriptions share a budget that scales at **~1% of the model's context window**. Raise it with the `skillListingBudgetFraction` setting (e.g. `0.02` = 2%) or the `SLASH_COMMAND_TOOL_CHAR_BUDGET` env var (fixed char count). When it overflows, the descriptions of the *least-used* skills get dropped first — silently stripping the keywords Claude needs to match them. Run `/doctor` to see what's being shortened or dropped. The lesson: front-load the trigger phrase in every `description`.\n\n### Gotcha: triggering vs. working\n\nSeeing a skill fire only tells you the description matched — not that the body did its job. If a skill seems to stop influencing behavior, the content is usually still present and the model is just choosing other tools; strengthen the `description`/body, or escalate to a hook for true enforcement. The docs prescribe a **baseline comparison**: run the same realistic prompts in a fresh session with the skill enabled and disabled, and compare. The official `skill-creator` plugin automates this A/B loop with per-case sub-agent isolation, writing pass-rate vs. token-overhead to `benchmark.json`.\n\n## Portable skills: author once, mirror into each tool\nYour team runs both Claude Code and Codex in VS Code. The good news: Agent Skills use the **open `SKILL.md` standard** that both tools build on (agentskills.io, developers.openai.com/codex/skills, code.claude.com/docs/en/skills). The catch: **each tool reads only its own skills directory.** There is no shared resolver.\n\n| Tool | Skills directory (project) | Skills directory (user) | Invocation |\n|------|---------------------------|------------------------|------------|\n| Claude Code | `.claude/skills/<name>/SKILL.md` | `~/.claude/skills/` | `/name` or model-matched on `description` |\n| Codex | `.agents/skills/<name>/SKILL.md` | `~/.agents/skills/` | `/skills`, `$name`, or model-matched on `description` |\n\nCodex's search order is: repo-level `.agents/skills` (current dir walking up to repo root) → `$HOME/.agents/skills` → `/etc/codex/skills` (admin) → built-ins. It uses the same progressive-disclosure model: name+description first (the initial skills list is capped at **~2% of context, or 8,000 characters**), full body on selection. Both tools require `name` + `description` frontmatter; same-named skills are *not* merged across scopes — both can appear in selectors.\n\n### Portability = author once, mirror into each dir\n\nThe core `SKILL.md` (frontmatter `name` + `description` + body) is identical across both tools. A **portable skill** is one written in that common subset and made discoverable in each tool's directory. The robust pattern: keep a single canonical source and project it.\n\n```text\n~/.agents/skills/             # canonical source of truth\n└── summarize-changes/\n    └── SKILL.md\n\n# Project it into each tool's discovery path (symlink or copy):\nln -s ~/.agents/skills/summarize-changes .claude/skills/summarize-changes\nln -s ~/.agents/skills/summarize-changes .agents/skills/summarize-changes\n```\n\n### Gotchas\n\n- **Claude-only frontmatter doesn't port.** `context: fork`, `disable-model-invocation`, `allowed-tools`, `disallowed-tools`, `argument-hint`, `paths` are Claude Code extensions to the standard. Codex ignores them. Keep portable skills to the common subset, or accept tool-specific behavior.\n- **A new top-level skills directory needs a restart.** Claude Code live-watches *existing* skill dirs (`~/.claude/skills/`, project `.claude/skills/`) for edits, but creating a *new* top-level dir mid-session requires restarting so it can be watched.\n- **Drift is invisible until it bites.** If you copy rather than symlink, the two dirs silently diverge. Gate it in CI — see the last section.\n\n## Sub-agents: a bounded mission in its own context\nA **sub-agent** *\"runs in its own context window with a custom system prompt, specific tool access, and independent permissions,\"* and *\"returns only the summary to the main context\"* (code.claude.com/docs/en/sub-agents). That last clause is the point: the sub-agent can read 40 files, run 12 greps, and burn 30k tokens — and your main conversation gets back three paragraphs, not the transcript.\n\nUse one when a side task would flood your main window with search results, logs, or file contents you won't reference again. Define a *reusable* one when you keep spawning the same kind of worker with the same instructions. (Claude Code also ships built-ins: `Explore` — Haiku, read-only, for codebase search; `Plan` — read-only research; `general-purpose` — all tools. `Explore`/`Plan` skip your CLAUDE.md and git status to stay cheap.)\n\n### File format\n\nMarkdown with YAML frontmatter, in `.claude/agents/` (project) or `~/.claude/agents/` (user). Only `name` and `description` are required:\n\n```yaml\n---\nname: safe-researcher\ndescription: Research agent with restricted, read-only capabilities. Use for codebase exploration that should not write files.\ntools: Read, Grep, Glob, Bash\nmodel: haiku\n---\n\nYou are a read-only research agent. Find relevant files, read them,\nand return a summary with specific file:line references. Never edit.\n```\n\nThe **markdown body becomes the sub-agent's entire system prompt** — it does not inherit the main Claude Code system prompt, only basic environment details.\n\n### The three levers\n\n| Lever | Field | Why it matters |\n|-------|-------|----------------|\n| **Least-privilege tools** | `tools:` (allowlist) or `disallowedTools:` (denylist) | Omit `tools` and the sub-agent inherits *all* tools. Set `tools: Read, Grep, Glob` to lock it to exactly the mission — never `Write` or `Edit`. Or invert with `disallowedTools: Write, Edit` to keep everything else. This is enforcement, not a suggestion. |\n| **Cheaper model** | `model:` | `sonnet` / `opus` / `haiku` / `fable` / a full ID / `inherit` (default). Route bounded grunt work to `ha"}, {"id": "stage-4", "title": "Sharing It: Plugins & Marketplace", "concepts": ["a plugin", "a plugin marketplace"], "claims": ["A Claude Code plugin can bundle slash commands, subagents, skills, hooks, MCP servers, and LSP servers into one installable unit.", "A plugin marketplace is a catalog repo defined by .claude-plugin/marketplace.json; teams add it once (/plugin marketplace add), install plugins (/plugin install), and pull updates (/plugin marketplace update).", "Installing a plugin activates its skills, hooks, and MCP servers as code under one trust decision; audits of open third-party marketplaces found malicious skills (Snyk: 76 confirmed malicious payloads among ~3,984 skills; 13.4% critical), and plugin-injection attacks are demonstrated."], "content": "## The shelf nobody built\nThree people on your team have written a code-review skill. One lives in Maya's `~/.claude/skills/review/`, one is copy-pasted into the `.claude/commands/` of the payments repo, and the third is a half-remembered prompt Devon keeps in a Notion doc. They are 80% the same and 20% subtly divergent — different severity ladders, different ideas about what \"done\" means. The waste was never the writing. Writing a good review skill once is cheap. The waste is that there is **no shelf everyone pulls from**, so the skill gets re-derived, drifts, and rots in three places at once.\n\nThis stage is about building that shelf. Claude Code's answer has two parts: a **plugin** (the unit you put *on* the shelf — a versioned bundle of skills, sub-agents, hooks, MCP servers, and LSP servers) and a **plugin marketplace** (the shelf itself — a catalog repo the team adds once and pulls updates from). By the end you will be able to take that scattered review skill, package it as a plugin, publish it in a private team marketplace, and have everyone install it with two commands — plus understand exactly what you are trusting when you do, because installing a plugin is one consent click over a lot of executable surface.\n\nThis is depth, not a tour. Every format below is copy-able and checked against the official docs at `code.claude.com/docs` (`/plugins`, `/plugin-marketplaces`, `/discover-plugins`, `/plugins-reference`).\n\n## What a plugin actually is\nA **plugin** is a versioned bundle of extensions — slash commands, sub-agents, skills, hooks, MCP servers, and LSP servers — packaged into one installable unit (source: `code.claude.com/docs/en/plugins`). It is the difference between \"here's a file, copy it into your `.claude/`\" and \"install `code-review@team-tools` and you have the same thing I have, with updates.\"\n\nThe docs frame the standalone-vs-plugin choice as a tradeoff over skill *names* and *sharing*: standalone `.claude/` skills get short names (`/review`); plugin skills are always namespaced (`/plugin-name:review`). Use standalone for personal/project-only iteration; reach for a plugin when you want versioned releases reusable across projects and teammates.\n\n### The minimum: a manifest\n\nEvery plugin is a directory. The defining file is the manifest at `.claude-plugin/plugin.json`:\n\n```json\n{\n  \"name\": \"code-review\",\n  \"description\": \"Team code-review skill: severity ladder, security pass, test-coverage check\",\n  \"version\": \"1.2.0\",\n  \"author\": { \"name\": \"DevTools Team\", \"email\": \"devtools@acme.com\" }\n}\n```\n\nFields that matter (from the official manifest table):\n\n| Field | Required | Why it matters |\n|---|---|---|\n| `name` | yes | Unique id **and** skill namespace. Skills become `/code-review:<skill>`. kebab-case, no spaces. |\n| `description` | recommended | Shown in the plugin manager when teammates browse. |\n| `version` | optional | If set, users only get updates when you **bump** it. If omitted on a git-hosted plugin, the commit SHA is used and every commit counts as a new version. |\n| `author` | optional | Attribution (`name` required, `email` optional). |\n\nThe manifest also accepts `homepage`, `repository`, `license`, and `keywords` (see the full manifest schema in `/plugins-reference`). The namespacing is deliberate: a plugin skill is *always* invoked as `/plugin-name:skill-name` (e.g. `/code-review:review`) so two plugins can both ship a `review` skill without colliding. You change the prefix by changing `name`.\n\nNote a subtlety from the docs: the manifest is technically *optional* if every component sits in its default location — a directory with just `skills/` can load. But for anything you intend to version and share, write the `plugin.json`; it is what the plugin manager displays and what drives version-based updates.\n\n## Plugin directory layout — and the one mistake everyone makes\nComponents live in fixed directories at the **plugin root**, not inside `.claude-plugin/`. This is the single most common authoring error, and the docs flag it explicitly with a Warning.\n\n```text\ncode-review/\n├── .claude-plugin/\n│   └── plugin.json          # ONLY this goes in .claude-plugin/\n├── skills/\n│   └── review/\n│       └── SKILL.md         # → /code-review:review\n├── agents/\n│   └── security-reviewer.md  # a sub-agent\n├── hooks/\n│   └── hooks.json            # event handlers\n├── monitors/\n│   └── monitors.json         # background watchers (tail logs, files, status)\n├── .mcp.json                 # MCP server configs\n├── .lsp.json                 # language-server configs\n├── commands/                 # legacy: flat .md skills (use skills/ for new work)\n├── bin/                      # executables added to PATH while enabled\n└── settings.json             # default settings when the plugin is enabled\n```\n\n| Directory / file | Location | Purpose |\n|---|---|---|\n| `.claude-plugin/plugin.json` | inside `.claude-plugin/` | the manifest — **the only thing** in here |\n| `skills/<name>/SKILL.md` | root | model-invoked skills |\n| `commands/*.md` | root | legacy flat-Markdown skills; docs say use `skills/` for new plugins |\n| `agents/*.md` | root | sub-agent definitions |\n| `hooks/hooks.json` | root | event handlers (PreToolUse, PostToolUse, …) |\n| `monitors/monitors.json` | root | background monitors; each `command`'s stdout lines become notifications |\n| `.mcp.json` | root | MCP server configs |\n| `.lsp.json` | root | LSP servers for code intelligence |\n| `bin/` | root | executables added to the Bash tool's `$PATH` while the plugin is enabled |\n| `settings.json` | root | default settings (only `agent` and `subagentStatusLine` honored; unknown keys silently ignored) |\n\nFrom the docs (verbatim Warning): *\"Don't put `commands/`, `agents/`, `skills/`, or `hooks/` inside the `.claude-plugin/` directory. Only `plugin.json` goes inside `.claude-plugin/`. All other directories must be at the plugin root level.\"* If your skills don't show up after install, this is the first thing to check.\n\nA plugin shipping exactly one skill may put `SKILL.md` at the plugin root and skip the `skills/` directory entirely (Claude Code uses the frontmatter `name` for the invocation); use the `skills/` layout once you expect more than one.\n\n## The components: what you can bundle\n### Skills\n\nA skill is a folder under `skills/` containing a `SKILL.md` with YAML frontmatter. The `description` is load-bearing — it's how Claude decides when to auto-invoke:\n\n```markdown\n---\ndescription: Reviews code for bugs, security, and performance. Use when reviewing code, checking PRs, or analyzing code quality.\n---\n\nWhen reviewing code, check for:\n1. Code organization and structure\n2. Error handling and edge cases\n3. Security concerns (injection, secrets, authz)\n4. Test coverage\n\nReport findings as severity-ranked, actionable items. Be concise.\n```\n\nAdd `disable-model-invocation: true` to the frontmatter (the docs use exactly this in their quickstart) if you want the skill to be *only* explicitly invokable (`/code-review:review`) and never auto-fired by the model. `$ARGUMENTS` in the body captures text the user types after the skill name (e.g. `/code-review:review src/auth.ts`).\n\n### Sub-agents\n\nDrop agent definitions in `agents/*.md`. A `settings.json` at the plugin root with `{\"agent\": \"security-reviewer\"}` can even make one of the plugin's agents the **main thread** when the plugin is enabled — applying its system prompt, tool restrictions, and model. That's a plugin that changes how Claude Code behaves by default. (Only `agent` and `subagentStatusLine` are honored in plugin `settings.json`; other keys are silently ignored.)\n\n### Hooks\n\nHooks live in `hooks/hooks.json` and use the exact same format as the `hooks` block in `settings.json` — so migration is copy-paste. The command receives hook input as JSON on stdin; the docs use `jq` to pull the file path out:\n\n```json\n{\n  \"hooks\": {\n    \"PostToolUse\": [\n      {\n        \"matcher\": \"Write|Edit\",\n        \"hooks\": [\n          { \"type\": \"command\", \"command\": \"${CLAUDE_PLUGIN_ROOT}/scripts/lint.sh\" }\n        ]\n      }\n    ]\n  }\n}\n```\n\n`${CLAUDE_PLUGIN_ROOT}` resolves to the plugin's installed (cached) location — use it for any path into the plugin, because plugins are **copied to a cache**, so `../shared-utils` and absolute author-machine paths will not resolve. For state that must *survive plugin updates* (a SQLite db, a token cache), use `${CLAUDE_PLUGIN_DATA}` instead — the cache directory is replaced on update, the data directory is not.\n\n### MCP servers\n\nBundle an MCP server config in `.mcp.json` (or inline `mcpServers` in the marketplace entry). This is how the official `github`, `linear`, `sentry`, `slack`, `notion`, `figma`, `vercel`, and `supabase` plugins ship pre-configured MCP integrations — install the plugin, get the server, no manual `.mcp.json` editing.\n\n### LSP servers\n\n`.lsp.json` wires a language server for real-time diagnostics and code navigation. The official marketplace already ships `pyright-lsp`, `gopls-lsp`, `typescript-lsp`, `rust-analyzer-lsp`, and more; author your own only for languages not covered. The user must have the language-server **binary** on `$PATH` — if it's missing you'll see `Executable not found in $PATH` in the `/plugin` Errors tab. Minimal `.lsp.json`:\n\n```json\n{ \"go\": { \"command\": \"gopls\", \"args\": [\"serve\"], \"extensionToLanguage\": { \".go\": \"go\" } } }\n```\n\n### Background monitors\n\n`monitors/monitors.json` lets a plugin watch a log, file, or external status in the background; each stdout line from the monitor's `command` is delivered to Claude as a notification during the session — no instruction to \"start watching\" needed.\n\n## Develop and test before you publish\nYou do not need a marketplace to iterate. Load a plugin straight off disk:\n\n```bash\nclaude --plugin-dir ./code-review\n```\n\nThen inside the session, after edits, pick up changes without restarting:\n\n```text\n/reload-plugins\n```\n\n`/reload-plugins` reloads plugins, skills, agents, hooks, and plugin MCP/LSP servers, and reports counts for each. Verify the three surfaces individually: run `/code-review:review`, confirm agents appear in `/agents`, and confirm hooks fire on a real edit.\n\nLoad several at once by repeating the flag: `claude --plugin-dir ./a --plugin-dir ./b`. When a `--plugin-dir` plugin shares a name with an installed marketplace plugin, the local copy wins for that session — so you can test a patch to something already installed without uninstalling it (exception: plugins force-enabled/disabled by managed settings can't be overridden this way). `--plugin-dir` also accepts a `.zip` archive (Claude Code v2.1.128+), and `--plugin-url https://…/plugin.zip` fetches and loads an archive for that session only.\n\nValidate the structure before you ship:\n\n```bash\nclaude plugin validate ./code-review     # or /plugin validate ./code-review in-session\n```\n\nPointed at a **plugin** directory, the validator checks `plugin.json` plus the frontmatter of every skill, agent, and command, and the JSON of `hooks/hooks.json`. Pointed at a **marketplace** directory, it checks `marketplace.json` only (schema, duplicate plugin names, `..` path traversal, version mismatches against each `plugin.json`). A malformed `hooks.json` prevents the **entire plugin** from loading, so this catches a real failure mode.\n\n### Converting your scattered skill\n\nMigrating the existing `.claude/` review skill is mechanical (these are the docs' own migration steps):\n\n```bash\nmkdir -p code-review/.claude-plugin\n# write plugin.json (above), then:\ncp -r .claude/skills/review code-review/skills/\n```\n\nHooks from a `settings.json` move verbatim into `hooks/hooks.json` (same format). Afterward, **delete the originals** from `.claude/` — project/user `.claude/agents/` definitions override same-named plugin agents, so leaving them creates silent shadowing.\n\nIf you'd rather skip `--plugin-dir` on every launch while iterating, `claude plugin init my-tool` scaffolds a plugin under `~/.claude/skills/my-tool/` that auto-loads next session as `my-tool@skills-dir`.\n\n## What a marketplace is\nA **plugin marketplace** is a catalog repo defined by a single file, `.claude-plugin/marketplace.json`, that lists plugins and where to fetch each one. Teams **add it once**, install the plugins they need, and pull updates by refreshing the catalog (sources: `code.claude.com/docs/en/plugin-marketplaces`, `/discover-plugins`).\n\nThe mental model from the docs: adding a marketplace is *\"like adding an app store\"* — it gives you the catalog to browse, but you still choose which plugins to install individually. Adding the marketplace installs **nothing**.\n\n### The catalog file\n\n```json\n{\n  \"name\": \"acme-tools\",\n  \"owner\": { \"name\": \"DevTools Team\", \"email\": \"devtools@acme.com\" },\n  \"plugins\": [\n    {\n      \"name\": \"code-review\",\n      \"source\": \"./plugins/code-review\",\n      \"description\": \"Team code-review skill\",\n      \"version\": \"1.2.0\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"name\": \"deploy-tools\",\n      \"source\": { \"source\": \"github\", \"repo\": \"acme/deploy-plugin\" },\n      \"description\": \"Deployment automation\"\n    }\n  ]\n}\n```\n\nRequired top-level fields are `name` (kebab-case, public-facing — it's the `@acme-tools` in `/plugin install x@acme-tools`), `owner` (object, `name` required, `email` optional), and `plugins` (array). Each plugin entry needs at minimum `name` and `source`. Useful optionals: `metadata.pluginRoot: \"./plugins\"` lets you write `\"source\": \"code-review\"` instead of `\"./plugins/code-review\"`; a plugin entry may also carry `displayName` (a spaced/cased human label, v2.1.143+) and `defaultEnabled: false` (install disabled until the user opts in, v2.1.154+).\n\nTwo constraints worth knowing up front: each user can register only **one marketplace per name** — adding a second with the same `name` replaces the first, so list all your plugins in one `marketplace.json`. And a set of names (`claude-plugins-official`, `claude-community`, `anthropic-*`, etc.) is **reserved** for Anthropic and rejected for third-party m"}, {"id": "stage-5", "title": "Governance & Plan", "concepts": ["managed settings", "settings precedence", "seats & plan gating", "a permission rule", "permission mode"], "claims": ["Computer use and phone Dispatch are a Pro/Max research preview (macOS and Windows); the docs do NOT document Team/Enterprise exclusion, so 'not on Team' is an inference, restated as 'not part of the documented Team plan'.", "Claude Code is included on every Team seat (Standard and Premium); Premium only buys more usage and is NOT the access gate. (A Premium/Code-seat requirement applies only to legacy Enterprise.)", "Settings precedence, highest to lowest: managed (org) > command-line args > local project (.claude/settings.local.json) > shared project (.claude/settings.json) > user (~/.claude/settings.json).", "Managed (enterprise-policy) settings sit at the top of precedence and cannot be overridden by a user, CLI flag, or project file.", "The managed-settings keys strictKnownMarketplaces, blockedMarketplaces, strictPluginOnlyCustomization, allowedMcpServers, wslInheritsWindowsSettings, and minimumVersion all exist and are enforced (plus allowManagedHooksOnly / allowManagedMcpServersOnly / allowManagedPermissionRulesOnly).", "Installing a plugin activates its skills, hooks, and MCP servers as code under one trust decision; audits of open third-party marketplaces found malicious skills (Snyk: 76 confirmed malicious payloads among ~3,984 skills; 13.4% critical), and plugin-injection attacks are demonstrated.", "Claude Code access control is allow/ask/deny permission rules — tool-name glob patterns (e.g. Bash(git push:*), Read(./.env.*), mcp__*) in settings.json permissions{}. Rules evaluate deny → ask → allow, first-match-wins; the allow/ask/deny arrays MERGE (concatenate) across scopes, so a higher-scope (managed or user) deny is a floor no lower scope can relax.", "Permission modes are an autonomy dial orthogonal to the rules: default (ask), plan (restricted to reads and read-only shell, proposes changes without editing), acceptEdits (auto-approve file edits + common fs commands in the working dir), auto (a classifier model approves/denies each call), and bypassPermissions (no prompts — and as of v2.1.126 even protected paths like .git/.claude execute). Set via defaultMode; cycle in-session with Shift+Tab."], "content": "## Why a CLAUDE.md note is not a control\nStage 4 gave the team a shared `CLAUDE.md`, skills, and a plugin or two. That file shapes what Claude *tries* to do. It does not change what Claude Code *allows*. The distinction is load-bearing, and the docs are blunt about it:\n\n> Permission rules are enforced by Claude Code, not by the model. Instructions in your prompt or `CLAUDE.md` shape what Claude tries to do, but they don't change what Claude Code allows. ([permissions docs](https://code.claude.com/docs/en/permissions))\n\nThis means every must-not you wrote in prose — \"never read `.env`\", \"don't `git push` to main\", \"don't install plugins from random marketplaces\" — is a *suggestion to a probabilistic system under adversarial pressure* (a prompt injection in a fetched web page, a malicious skill, a confused autocomplete). The model can be talked out of a CLAUDE.md rule. It cannot be talked out of a deny rule, because the deny rule lives in the harness and is evaluated before the tool call runs.\n\nGovernance is the act of moving the must-nots out of prose and into three enforcement layers:\n\n- **Permission rules** — allow/ask/deny glob patterns the harness checks on every tool call.\n- **Permission modes** — the autonomy dial that sets the baseline for how often it even asks.\n- **Managed settings** — org-level policy that sits *above* everything a developer can change, so a lower scope cannot relax it.\n\nThe second half of this stage is the money side of governance: **seats and plan gating** — making sure you are not budgeting for access you already have, or assuming a feature is in your plan when it is a research preview. Both halves answer the same question: what does the *system* guarantee, independent of any individual's good intentions?\n\n## Settings precedence: the resolution order that makes governance possible\nClaude Code reads configuration from five scopes and resolves them in a fixed order. Highest wins:\n\n| Rank | Scope | File | Who controls it |\n|------|-------|------|-----------------|\n| 1 (highest) | **Managed** | `/etc/claude-code/managed-settings.json` (Linux/WSL), `/Library/Application Support/ClaudeCode/managed-settings.json` (macOS), `C:\\Program Files\\ClaudeCode\\managed-settings.json` (Windows) | Org admin / MDM |\n| 2 | **Command-line args** | `--permission-mode`, `--allowedTools`, `--disallowedTools`, etc. | Whoever launches the session |\n| 3 | **Local project** | `.claude/settings.local.json` (gitignored) | Individual dev, this machine |\n| 4 | **Shared project** | `.claude/settings.json` (committed) | The team, via the repo |\n| 5 (lowest) | **User** | `~/.claude/settings.json` | Individual dev, all projects |\n\nSource: [settings docs](https://code.claude.com/docs/en/settings). The legacy Windows path `C:\\ProgramData\\ClaudeCode\\managed-settings.json` is **no longer supported as of v2.1.75** — if you wrote MDM tooling against it, it silently stops applying. Migrate deployments to `C:\\Program Files\\ClaudeCode\\managed-settings.json`.\n\n### Two different merge behaviors — do not conflate them\n\nFor *most* scalar settings (`model`, `outputStyle`, `defaultMode`), higher precedence **overrides** lower: managed `model` beats user `model`, full stop.\n\nBut **permission rules do not override — they merge (concatenate)** across all five scopes. This is the single most important mechanical fact in this stage and the reason governance is enforceable. It gets its own section below.\n\n### The governance lever\n\nBecause managed settings sit at rank 1 and *cannot be overridden by a CLI flag* (rank 2), a managed deny rule is a hard floor. A developer cannot pass `--allowedTools 'Read(./.env.*)'` to climb over a managed `deny`. The docs are explicit: \"a managed settings deny cannot be overridden by `--allowedTools`, and `--disallowedTools` can add restrictions beyond what managed settings define.\" That is what makes managed settings a *control* and not a *default*.\n\n## Permission rules: the access-control primitive\nA permission rule is a tool-name glob pattern living in the `permissions` object of a settings file. Three arrays:\n\n```json\n{\n  \"permissions\": {\n    \"allow\": [\n      \"Bash(npm run *)\",\n      \"Bash(git commit *)\",\n      \"Read(~/.zshrc)\"\n    ],\n    \"ask\": [\n      \"Bash(git push *)\"\n    ],\n    \"deny\": [\n      \"Read(./.env)\",\n      \"Read(./.env.*)\",\n      \"Read(./secrets/**)\",\n      \"Bash(curl *)\"\n    ]\n  }\n}\n```\n\nManage them live with `/permissions`, which lists every rule and the settings file it came from.\n\n### Rule shape\n\nA rule is `Tool` or `Tool(specifier)`. A bare tool name matches every use:\n\n- `Bash` — every shell command. `Bash(*)` is equivalent. As a **deny** rule, a bare name *removes the tool from Claude's context entirely* — Claude never even sees it. A scoped rule like `Bash(rm *)` leaves Bash available and blocks only matching calls.\n- `Bash(git push *)` — commands starting with `git push`. The space before `*` enforces a word boundary: `Bash(ls *)` matches `ls -la` but **not** `lsof`; `Bash(ls*)` matches both. `Bash(ls:*)` is an equivalent trailing-wildcard form (the `:*` suffix is only recognized at the *end* of a pattern). A single `*` spans multiple arguments, so `Bash(git * main)` matches `git push origin main` and `git merge main`.\n- `Read(./.env.*)` — file reads follow [gitignore semantics](https://code.claude.com/docs/en/permissions). A bare filename matches at any depth: `Read(.env)` == `Read(**/.env)`. Anchors matter: `/path` is **relative to project root**, `//path` is a true absolute path, `~/path` is home, and a bare `path` or `./path` is **relative to the current directory**. `Read(/Users/alice/x)` is NOT absolute — it is `<project>/Users/alice/x`; use `Read(//Users/alice/x)` for the real absolute path.\n- `WebFetch(domain:example.com)` — matches the hostname (case-insensitive). `WebFetch(domain:*.example.com)` matches subdomains at any depth but **not** the apex `example.com`.\n- `mcp__github` / `mcp__github__*` / `mcp__github__get_*` — MCP tools. The allow-side server segment must be glob-free. `mcp__*` (a tool-name glob) in a **deny** array kills every MCP tool across every server; as an *allow* glob, `mcp__*` is skipped with a warning and auto-approves nothing.\n\n### Compound commands and process wrappers\n\nClaude Code is shell-aware: a rule like `Bash(safe-cmd *)` does **not** authorize `safe-cmd && other-cmd` — each subcommand (split on `&&`, `||`, `;`, `|`, `&`, newlines) must match independently. A fixed set of wrappers is stripped before matching, so `Bash(npm test *)` also matches `timeout 30 npm test` (recognized wrappers: `timeout`, `time`, `nice`, `nohup`, `stdbuf`, and bare `xargs`). Environment-runner wrappers like `npx`, `docker exec`, `devbox run`, and `mise exec` are **not** stripped — `Bash(devbox run *)` would match `devbox run rm -rf .`, so write an explicit inner rule like `Bash(devbox run npm test)`.\n\n### Match by input parameter (deny/ask only)\n\nA newer form, `Tool(param:value)`, matches a top-level scalar input parameter — useful for autonomy gating: `Agent(model:opus)`, `Agent(isolation:worktree)`, `Bash(run_in_background:true)`. This is **deny/ask only** — an allow rule for one parameter wouldn't establish the whole call is safe. The value supports `*` as a wildcard; a parameter the model omits is never matched (so `Agent(model:*)` does not match a call that leaves `model` unset). Canonicalized fields (`command` for Bash, `file_path` for Read/Edit/Write, `url` for WebFetch, `path` for Grep/Glob) are *not* matchable this way — `Bash(command:rm *)` is ignored with a startup warning; use `Bash(rm *)`.\n\nAll of the above is verified against the [permissions docs](https://code.claude.com/docs/en/permissions).\n\n## How rules evaluate: deny → ask → allow, first-match-wins, arrays merge\nThis is the algorithm. Memorize it; it is the whole enforcement model.\n\n### Evaluation order\n\nRules are checked in the order **deny, then ask, then allow**. The first match in that order wins, and **specificity does not change the order**:\n\n> A broad deny rule like `Bash(aws *)` blocks every matching call, including calls that also match a narrower allow rule like `Bash(aws s3 ls)`, so a deny rule cannot carry allowlist exceptions. ([permissions docs](https://code.claude.com/docs/en/permissions))\n\nSo you cannot write `deny: Bash(aws *)` + `allow: Bash(aws s3 ls)` and expect the narrow allow to punch through. Deny is absolute for anything it matches. The same precedence holds between ask and allow: a matching `ask` rule prompts even when a more specific `allow` also matches. If you need exceptions, you invert: allow the safe specifics, and use a `PreToolUse` hook or a narrower deny for the dangerous ones.\n\n### Arrays merge across scopes — the floor property\n\nThe `allow`/`ask`/`deny` arrays from **all five scopes are concatenated** before evaluation. Combined with deny-first, this gives the property that makes org governance real:\n\n> If a tool is denied at any level, no other level can allow it. ([permissions docs](https://code.claude.com/docs/en/permissions))\n\nWork the direction both ways:\n\n- A **managed** `deny: Read(./.env.*)` is a floor. No user, project, local, or CLI allow can lift it. This is the mechanism behind \"deny secret reads\" org-wide.\n- A **user** `deny` also floors a **project** `allow`. If a dev personally denies `Bash(git push *)` in `~/.claude/settings.json`, a repo's committed `allow: Bash(git push *)` cannot override it — deny from any scope is evaluated before any allow.\n\n### A worked trace\n\nManaged: `deny: [\"Read(./.env.*)\"]`. Project: `allow: [\"Read(./**)\"]`. Claude tries to read `./.env.production`:\n\n1. Merged deny array contains `Read(./.env.*)` → matches `./.env.production` → **denied**. Allow is never consulted. The project's broad allow is irrelevant.\n\nThis is why you put the secret-read denials and the destructive-command denials in **managed** settings, not the repo: the repo is editable by anyone with commit access; managed settings are not.\n\n## Permission modes: the orthogonal autonomy dial\nPermission *rules* answer *what is allowed*. Permission *modes* answer *how aggressively Claude acts on what's allowed* — how often it pauses to ask at all. They are orthogonal: a mode sets the baseline, rules layer on top, and **deny rules and explicit `ask` rules apply in every mode, including `bypassPermissions`** (allow rules have no effect in `bypassPermissions` because everything is already approved).\n\n| Mode | Runs without asking | Best for | Set via |\n|------|---------------------|----------|---------|\n| `default` | Reads only | Sensitive work, getting started | baseline |\n| `plan` | Reads + read-only shell (no edits at all; proposes a plan) | Exploring before changing | `Shift+Tab`, `/plan`, `--permission-mode plan` |\n| `acceptEdits` | Reads + file edits + common fs commands (`mkdir`, `touch`, `rm`, `rmdir`, `mv`, `cp`, `sed`) in-scope | Iterating on code you'll review via `git diff` | `Shift+Tab`, flag, `defaultMode` |\n| `auto` | Everything, with a classifier model checking each call | Long tasks, reducing prompt fatigue | `--permission-mode auto`, admin-gated |\n| `dontAsk` | Only pre-approved (allow rules + read-only Bash); everything else auto-**denied** | Locked-down CI | `--permission-mode dontAsk` |\n| `bypassPermissions` | Everything, no prompts | Isolated containers/VMs only | `--permission-mode bypassPermissions` / `--dangerously-skip-permissions` |\n\nSource: [permission-modes docs](https://code.claude.com/docs/en/permission-modes).\n\n### Setting and cycling\n\n```json\n{ \"permissions\": { \"defaultMode\": \"plan\" } }\n```\n\nIn-session, `Shift+Tab` cycles `default → acceptEdits → plan`. The other modes are deliberately *not* in the default cycle: `auto` slots in only when your account qualifies and you opt in; `bypassPermissions` appears only after you started with an enabling flag (`--permission-mode bypassPermissions`, `--dangerously-skip-permissions`, or `--allow-dangerously-skip-permissions`); `dontAsk` never appears in the cycle at all and must be set with `--permission-mode dontAsk`.\n\n### Protected paths — never auto-approved except in bypass\n\nWrites to a fixed set of protected paths are **never auto-approved in any mode except `bypassPermissions`** — and crucially, a `permissions.allow` rule does **not** pre-approve them (the safety check runs *before* allow rules). The set is broader than just `.git` and `.claude`: it includes `.config/git`, `.vscode`, `.idea`, `.husky`, `.cargo`, `.devcontainer`, `.yarn`, `.mvn`, plus files like `.gitconfig`, `.zshrc`, `.npmrc`, `.envrc`, `.mcp.json`, and `.claude.json`. In `auto` mode these route to the classifier; in `dontAsk` they are denied; in prompting modes you get a prompt.\n\n### The two notes that bite teams\n\n- **`defaultMode: \"auto\"` is ignored from project/local settings.** As of v2.1.142, Claude Code ignores `auto` set in `.claude/settings.json` or `.claude/settings.local.json` so a repository cannot grant itself auto mode. It must live in `~/.claude/settings.json` or managed settings.\n- **`bypassPermissions` got more dangerous in v2.1.126.** It now executes writes to protected paths like `.git/` and `.claude/` that earlier versions still prompted for. Only `rm -rf /`, `rm -rf ~`, and explicit `ask` rules still stop it.\n\n## auto mode: a classifier, not a free pass\n`auto` mode is worth its own section because teams reach for it to \"reduce prompts\" and misjudge what it guarantees. It is a **research preview** and requires **Claude Code v2.1.83 or later** ([permission-modes docs](https://code.claude.com/docs/en/permission-modes)).\n\n### What it actually does\n\nInstead of prompting you, a **separate classifier model** reviews each non-trivial action before it runs and blocks anything that \"escalates beyond your request, targets unrecognized infrastructure, or appears driven by hostile content Claude read.\" Reads and working-directory edits (outside protected paths) skip the classifier; shell commands and network calls go through it — adding a "}, {"id": "stage-6", "title": "Decide: Your Team's Shared Setup", "concepts": ["the four-tier model", "a shared library"], "claims": ["Shared team setup falls into four tiers by where each thing lives: project config in the repo (.claude/), cross-project tools in a plugin marketplace, org policy in managed settings, and personal config local to each user.", "A team's shared library is one set of skills/agents/tools distributed via a plugin marketplace plus repo .claude/ + AGENTS.md, made portable across Claude Code and Codex — the assembled output of the four tiers."], "content": "## The decision you're actually making\nBy now you know the parts: skills, subagents, hooks, MCP servers, permission rules, `AGENTS.md`. That was the *vocabulary*. This stage is the *grammar* — the rule that tells you where each part goes so a five-person team (or fifty) shares one coherent setup instead of fifty divergent ones.\n\nThe question your team is waiting on is not \"what is a skill?\" It is: **when someone writes a useful skill, where does it live so everyone gets it, it stays versioned, and it works whether they drive Claude Code or Codex?** Get this wrong and you hit the two classic failure modes:\n\n- **Sprawl** — every engineer hand-copies skills into their own `~/.claude/`, they drift, and \"works on my machine\" infects your agent tooling.\n- **Lock-in** — everything lives in one person's local config, nobody can review it, and onboarding a new hire is a 40-minute Slack thread.\n\nThe fix is a single mental model: **the four-tier model**. Decide the tier for each shared thing *once*, write it down, and the rest is mechanics. The verified team-setup guidance ([Anthropic, *Steering Claude Code*](https://claude.com/blog/steering-claude-code-skills-hooks-rules-subagents-and-more); [*Settings*](https://code.claude.com/docs/en/settings)) is exactly this: shared setup falls into four tiers by **where each thing lives**.\n\n## The four-tier model\nEvery shared artifact belongs to exactly one of four tiers, distinguished by **scope of ownership** and **distribution mechanism**:\n\n| Tier | What lives here | Mechanism | Who owns it | Committed to git? |\n|------|----------------|-----------|-------------|-------------------|\n| **1. Project config** | Rules, project-specific skills/agents, hooks, permission allowlist, marketplace declaration | `.claude/` dir + `CLAUDE.md`/`AGENTS.md` in the repo | The repo / its maintainers | Yes — in the repo |\n| **2. Cross-project tools** | Skills, agents, MCP servers, hooks reused across many repos | A **plugin marketplace** (a git repo of plugins) | A platform/devtools team | Yes — in the marketplace repo |\n| **3. Org policy** | Mandatory guardrails: which MCP servers are allowed, version floors, forced login org, marketplace allowlist | **Managed settings** (`managed-settings.json`, MDM) | IT / security | Deployed by IT, not editable by users |\n| **4. Personal config** | Individual preferences: model choice, theme, personal experimental skills | `~/.claude/settings.json`, `~/.codex/config.toml` | Each engineer | No — local only |\n\n### The decision rule\n\nAsk these questions in order; the first \"yes\" picks the tier:\n\n1. **Is it a non-negotiable the org must enforce?** → Tier 3 (managed settings — it sits at the top of precedence and can't be overridden).\n2. **Is it reused across repos by the team?** → Tier 2 (marketplace plugin).\n3. **Is it specific to one repo?** → Tier 1 (project config in `.claude/`).\n4. Otherwise → Tier 4 (personal).\n\n### Precedence at runtime\n\nThe tiers also map onto a **precedence order** when settings collide. Per [the settings docs](https://code.claude.com/docs/en/settings), Claude Code resolves settings highest-to-lowest:\n\n**Managed → command-line args → Local → Project → User.**\n\nManaged (Tier 3) always wins; personal *user-scope* defaults (Tier 4) lose to everything. Note one wrinkle: a repo's `.claude/settings.local.json` is the **Local** scope, which *outranks* the committed Project `.claude/settings.json` — so a personal per-repo override beats the team's committed project setting, but still loses to managed. This precedence is deliberate: org policy can't be overridden by a clever engineer, and a personal experiment in one repo doesn't silently leak into the team's shared config.\n\nOne exception runs through everything below: **permission rules merge, they don't override** (covered in Tier 1).\n\n## Tier 1 — Project config in the repo\nThis is the tier most teams already half-have. Everything that is *true about this repo specifically* lives in `.claude/` and is committed, so cloning the repo gives you a fully-configured agent.\n\n### Layout\n\n```text\nmy-service/\n├── CLAUDE.md                 # rules/context for Claude Code\n├── AGENTS.md                 # same role for Codex & other agents (see portability)\n└── .claude/\n    ├── settings.json         # committed: team-shared settings (Project scope)\n    ├── settings.local.json   # gitignored: personal per-repo overrides (Local scope)\n    ├── skills/\n    │   └── run-migrations/SKILL.md\n    ├── agents/\n    │   └── db-reviewer.md\n    └── hooks/                # hook scripts; the hook *declarations* live in settings.json\n```\n\n### Committed vs local\n\nThe single most important split inside Tier 1: **`.claude/settings.json` is committed and shared (Project scope); `.claude/settings.local.json` is gitignored and personal (Local scope)** ([Settings docs](https://code.claude.com/docs/en/settings)). Put the team's permission allowlist, env vars, and hooks in `settings.json`. Put your personal one-off allows in `settings.local.json` — and remember Local outranks Project, so your local file wins any conflict with the committed one.\n\n```json\n// .claude/settings.json — committed, the whole team gets this\n{\n  \"$schema\": \"https://json.schemastore.org/claude-code-settings.json\",\n  \"permissions\": {\n    \"allow\": [\"Bash(npm run test:*)\", \"Bash(npm run lint)\"],\n    \"deny\": [\"Read(./.env)\", \"Read(./.env.*)\", \"Read(./secrets/**)\"],\n    \"ask\": [\"Bash(git push:*)\"]\n  },\n  \"env\": { \"NODE_ENV\": \"development\" }\n}\n```\n\n### Permissions merge — they don't override\n\nThe one setting that breaks the precedence-override rule: **permission rules (`allow`/`ask`/`deny`) merge across every scope rather than override** ([Settings docs](https://code.claude.com/docs/en/settings)). A project `deny` and a managed `deny` both apply; arrays from all tiers combine. That's why a project can safely *add* `deny` rules on top of org policy without weakening it — and why a project **cannot remove** an org-level `deny`. Layered, additive guardrails are the design intent.\n\n## Tier 2 — Cross-project tools in a marketplace\nThis is the tier that turns \"I wrote a nice skill\" into \"the team has it.\" When a skill, agent, or MCP integration is useful across repos, you do **not** copy it into each `.claude/`. You package it as a **plugin** and distribute it through a **plugin marketplace** ([Create plugins](https://code.claude.com/docs/en/plugins); [Marketplaces](https://code.claude.com/docs/en/plugin-marketplaces)).\n\n### Why a marketplace instead of copying\n\n| Use standalone `.claude/` (Tier 1) | Use a plugin/marketplace (Tier 2) |\n|------------------------------------|-----------------------------------|\n| Single project | Reused across multiple projects |\n| Personal / experimental | Shared with the team or community |\n| Short skill names (`/deploy`) | Versioned, namespaced (`/my-plugin:deploy`) |\n| Manual copy to share | `/plugin install`, central updates |\n\nA marketplace gives you **centralized discovery, version tracking, automatic updates, and one source of truth.** Bump the version in one repo; every engineer's next `/plugin update` (or background auto-update) pulls it. No drift.\n\n### Anatomy of a plugin\n\nA plugin is a directory with a manifest in `.claude-plugin/` plus component dirs *at the plugin root* — **not** inside `.claude-plugin/`:\n\n```text\nquality-tools/\n├── .claude-plugin/\n│   └── plugin.json          # ONLY the manifest goes here\n├── skills/\n│   └── code-review/SKILL.md\n├── agents/\n│   └── security-reviewer.md\n├── hooks/\n│   └── hooks.json\n└── .mcp.json                # MCP servers the plugin ships\n```\n\n```json\n// .claude-plugin/plugin.json\n{\n  \"name\": \"quality-tools\",\n  \"description\": \"Shared code-review skill + security agent\",\n  \"version\": \"1.2.0\",\n  \"author\": { \"name\": \"DevTools Team\" }\n}\n```\n\nThe `name` becomes the namespace: this plugin's `code-review` skill is invoked `/quality-tools:code-review`. Namespacing is what keeps two teams' `deploy` skills from colliding. Inside hooks and MCP configs, reference files with `${CLAUDE_PLUGIN_ROOT}` — the plugin is copied to a cache on install, so relative-to-cwd paths won't resolve (more in Pitfalls).\n\n## Tier 2 mechanics — the marketplace file\nA **marketplace** is itself just a git repo containing a catalog at `.claude-plugin/marketplace.json` that lists plugins and where to fetch each one ([Marketplaces](https://code.claude.com/docs/en/plugin-marketplaces)). Required top-level fields are `name`, `owner` (with a required `owner.name`), and `plugins`.\n\n```json\n// .claude-plugin/marketplace.json\n{\n  \"name\": \"acme-tools\",\n  \"owner\": { \"name\": \"DevTools Team\", \"email\": \"devtools@acme.com\" },\n  \"plugins\": [\n    {\n      \"name\": \"quality-tools\",\n      \"source\": \"./plugins/quality-tools\",\n      \"description\": \"Code review + security agent\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"name\": \"deploy-tools\",\n      \"source\": { \"source\": \"github\", \"repo\": \"acme-corp/deploy-plugin\" }\n    }\n  ]\n}\n```\n\n### Plugin source types (the load-bearing field)\n\nEach plugin's `source` says where to fetch *that plugin*. (Distinct from the *marketplace* source — where the catalog itself lives — which supports `ref` but not `sha`.) The choices:\n\n| `source` | Form | Use when |\n|----------|------|----------|\n| Relative path | `\"./plugins/x\"` (must start with `./`, resolved from the marketplace root) | Plugin lives in the same marketplace repo |\n| `github` | `{ \"source\": \"github\", \"repo\": \"org/repo\", \"ref\": \"v2\", \"sha\": \"<40-char>\" }` | Plugin in a separate GitHub repo |\n| `url` | `{ \"source\": \"url\", \"url\": \"https://gitlab.com/...git\", \"ref\": \"...\", \"sha\": \"...\" }` | Any git host (`.git` suffix optional) |\n| `git-subdir` | `{ \"source\": \"git-subdir\", \"url\": \"...\", \"path\": \"tools/plugin\" }` | Plugin in a **monorepo** subdir (sparse clone) |\n| `npm` | `{ \"source\": \"npm\", \"package\": \"@acme/plugin\", \"version\": \"^2.0\", \"registry\": \"https://npm.example.com\" }` | Distribute via npm (public or private registry) |\n\n### Versioning — the part teams get wrong\n\nClaude Code resolves a plugin's version from the first of these that is set: (1) `version` in `plugin.json`, (2) `version` in the marketplace entry, (3) the git commit SHA of the source.\n\n- **For internal, fast-iterating plugins, omit `version` entirely** on git-based sources (`github`/`url`/`git-subdir`/relative-in-git). Every commit then counts as a new version — the simplest setup.\n- **For stable releases, set `version` in `plugin.json` and bump it on every release.** If `plugin.json` says `\"1.0.0\"` and you push new commits *without* changing it, existing users get **nothing** — Claude Code sees the same version and keeps the cache.\n- **Never set `version` in both `plugin.json` and the marketplace entry** — the `plugin.json` value wins *silently* and can mask the marketplace one.\n- **Pin with `sha` for reproducibility.** When both `ref` and `sha` are set, the `sha` is the effective pin; on GitHub/GitLab/Bitbucket the install survives even if the branch named by `ref` is later deleted (some hosts like AWS CodeCommit can't fetch by SHA, so there the `ref` must still exist).\n\n### Installing\n\n```shell\n/plugin marketplace add acme-corp/claude-plugins   # GitHub owner/repo shorthand (append @ref to pin)\n/plugin install quality-tools@acme-tools           # plugin@marketplace\n/plugin marketplace update                          # pull new versions\n```\n\nNon-interactive equivalents exist for CI and scripting:\n\n```bash\nclaude plugin marketplace add acme-corp/claude-plugins --scope project\nclaude plugin install quality-tools@acme-tools\nclaude plugin validate .   # run this in CI before publishing\n```\n\n`--scope project` writes the declaration into the committed `.claude/settings.json` (the Tier-1/Tier-2 bridge below), rather than the per-user default.\n\n## Tier 2 — making the marketplace mandatory for the team\nDiscovery is good, but you don't want onboarding to depend on each engineer remembering to run `/plugin marketplace add`. You make the marketplace **part of the repo** so that trusting the project folder prompts installation automatically ([Marketplaces → Require for your team](https://code.claude.com/docs/en/plugin-marketplaces)).\n\nThis is the bridge between Tier 1 and Tier 2: the marketplace *lives* in Tier 2, but the *declaration that this repo uses it* is committed Tier-1 project config in `.claude/settings.json`:\n\n```json\n// .claude/settings.json  (committed)\n{\n  \"extraKnownMarketplaces\": {\n    \"acme-tools\": {\n      \"source\": { \"source\": \"github\", \"repo\": \"acme-corp/claude-plugins\" }\n    }\n  },\n  \"enabledPlugins\": {\n    \"quality-tools@acme-tools\": true,\n    \"deploy-tools@acme-tools\": true\n  }\n}\n```\n\nNow a new hire clones the repo, trusts the folder, and Claude Code prompts them to install exactly the plugins the team relies on. `enabledPlugins` decides which are on by default.\n\n### Gotcha: marketplace state is per-user, not per-project\n\nMarketplace registrations live once per user in `~/.claude/plugins/known_marketplaces.json`, and each plugin is copied into a versioned cache under `~/.claude/plugins/cache`. Consequences:\n\n- A plugin **cannot** reference files outside its own directory (no `../shared-utils`) — they aren't copied. Use `${CLAUDE_PLUGIN_ROOT}` for in-plugin paths, or symlinks for genuinely shared assets.\n- For containers/CI, pre-seed with `CLAUDE_CODE_PLUGIN_SEED_DIR`. Build the seed once (run Claude Code, install the plugins, copy `~/.claude/plugins`), then point the variable at it. The seed mirrors `~/.claude/plugins`:\n\n```text\n$CLAUDE_CODE_PLUGIN_SEED_DIR/\n  known_marketplaces.json\n  marketplaces/<name>/...\n  cache/<marketplace>/<plugin>/<version>/...\n```\n\nThe seed is **read-only** (auto-updates are disabled for it) and its entries take precedence over the user's config on each startup, so the image starts fully provisioned and clones nothing at runtime.\n\n## Tier 3 — Org policy in managed settings\nTiers 1 and 2 are *opt-in conveniences*. Tier 3 is *enforcement*. Managed settings are deployed by IT (MDM, or a file dropped by "}];

// __QUIZ_INPUTS__ (injected)
const stages = QUIZ_INPUTS;
log(`authoring quizzes for ${stages.length} stages`);

const QUIZ = {
  type: "object", additionalProperties: false, required: ["questions"],
  properties: {
    questions: {
      type: "array", description: "5-7 rigorous questions",
      items: {
        type: "object", additionalProperties: false,
        required: ["type", "prompt", "options", "correct", "explanation", "testedConcept", "contentSource"],
        properties: {
          type: { type: "string", description: "single (one right answer) or multi (select all that apply)" },
          prompt: { type: "string" },
          options: {
            type: "array",
            description: "3-5 options. For each WRONG option you MUST include a misconceptionTargeted field in the optionMetadata array (same index) naming the real belief it encodes.",
            items: { type: "string" },
          },
          optionMetadata: {
            type: "array",
            description: "parallel to options — one entry per option. For correct options, misconceptionTargeted is empty string. For wrong options, misconceptionTargeted MUST be non-empty: describe the real misconception this distractor catches.",
            items: {
              type: "object", additionalProperties: false, required: ["misconceptionTargeted"],
              properties: { misconceptionTargeted: { type: "string" } },
            },
          },
          correct: { type: "array", items: { type: "integer" }, description: "indices of the correct option(s); one for single, one-or-more for multi" },
          explanation: { type: "string", description: "why the answer is right AND why the tempting distractors are wrong" },
          testedConcept: { type: "string", description: "the specific concept term or claim this question tests" },
          contentSource: { type: "string", description: "REQUIRED: the exact sentence or claim from the CONTENT or VERIFIED CLAIMS that makes the correct answer true. Quote it directly. If you cannot find a quote, the question is testing unverified content — rewrite it." },
        },
      },
    },
  },
};

const A = { agentType: "general-purpose", effort: "high" };

const out = {};
const results = await pipeline(
  stages,
  (s) => agent(
    `Write 5-7 RIGOROUS assessment questions for this stage of a course on setting up a team's shared Claude Code + Codex infrastructure. The current quiz was rejected as "trivial and obvious" — recognition-level recall. Yours must be HARD in the right way:\n` +
    `- Require APPLICATION and DISTINGUISHING subtle cases, not definition recall. At least 3 of 7 questions MUST be scenarios: "A teammate does X and Y happens — why?" / "Which of these belongs in managed settings vs project settings vs a plugin?" / "You expected A, got B — what changed?"\n` +
    `- Every WRONG option must encode a COMMON MISCONCEPTION (a plausible belief a real practitioner holds), not an obvious throwaway. Fill the optionMetadata[i].misconceptionTargeted field for every wrong option with the specific misconception it catches.\n` +
    `- Include at least two "select all that apply" (type=multi) questions.\n` +
    `- GROUNDING RULE: Every question's correct answer MUST be traceable to a specific sentence in the CONTENT or a specific VERIFIED CLAIM below. Fill contentSource with the exact quote. If you cannot quote it, the question tests unverified content — remove or rewrite it.\n` +
    `- PROHIBITION: Do not write questions that hinge on specific version numbers (v2.x.x), exact env var names, or exact file paths UNLESS those exact strings appear word-for-word in the CONTENT or VERIFIED CLAIMS below. Test behavior, not trivia about implementation details.\n` +
    `- Each explanation must say why the right answer is right AND why the tempting distractors are wrong.\n\n` +
    `STAGE: ${s.title} (${s.id})\nKEY CONCEPTS: ${s.concepts.join(", ")}\n\nVERIFIED CLAIMS:\n` +
    s.claims.map((c) => `- ${c}`).join("\n") +
    `\n\nDEEP CONTENT (the material learners just read):\n${s.content}`,
    { ...A, schema: QUIZ, label: `quiz:${s.id}`, phase: "Quiz" },
  ),
);
// --- normalise main quiz output ---
stages.forEach((s, i) => { const r = results[i]; if (r && Array.isArray(r.questions)) out[s.id] = r.questions; });
log(`main quizzes — ${Object.entries(out).map(([k, v]) => `${k}:${v.length}`).join(" ")}`);

// --- Phase 2: pre-quiz + tasks per stage (pipeline, same order) ---

const PRE_SCHEMA = {
  type: "object", additionalProperties: false, required: ["preQuiz", "tasks"],
  properties: {
    preQuiz: {
      type: "array",
      description: "Diagnostic questions shown BEFORE the lesson to let learners skip sections they already know. Enough questions to discriminate which sections they know — not an arbitrary limit. HARD: encode real misconceptions, no trivial distractors.",
      items: {
        type: "object", additionalProperties: false,
        required: ["prompt", "options", "correct", "sectionIndices", "explanation"],
        properties: {
          prompt: { type: "string", description: "Direct diagnostic question. NOT 'what is X' — instead test understanding: 'Your team sets up X. What happens when...' Reveal real gaps, not recall." },
          options: { type: "array", items: { type: "string" }, description: "3-4 options. Every wrong option must encode a REAL misconception practitioners hold — not an obviously-wrong throwaway." },
          correct: { type: "integer", description: "Index of the correct option (0-based)." },
          sectionIndices: { type: "array", items: { type: "integer" }, description: "Indices (0-based) of lesson sections this question covers. Correct answer → those sections collapse by default." },
          explanation: { type: "string", description: "Short explanation (1-2 sentences) of why the correct answer is right. Shown after answering." },
        },
      },
    },
    tasks: {
      type: "array",
      description: "Hands-on tasks — 'go set this up in Claude Code, come back when done'. 1-3 per stage. Each placed after a specific lesson section. Non-blocking.",
      items: {
        type: "object", additionalProperties: false,
        required: ["id", "afterSectionIdx", "title", "instructions", "doneWhen"],
        properties: {
          id: { type: "string", description: "unique kebab-case id, e.g. stage-0-task-auth" },
          afterSectionIdx: { type: "integer", description: "Index (0-based) of the lesson section this task follows." },
          title: { type: "string", description: "Short action-oriented title, e.g. 'Set up non-interactive auth for CI'" },
          instructions: { type: "string", description: "Markdown step-by-step: concrete commands/files to touch. Real actionable steps, not hand-waving. Use code fences for commands." },
          doneWhen: { type: "string", description: "One sentence: what the learner should have when they are done, verifiable by them." },
        },
      },
    },
  },
};

log(`authoring pre-quizzes + tasks for ${stages.length} stages`);
const preResults = await pipeline(
  stages,
  (s) => {
    const sections = (out[s.id] ?? []);
    const sectionCount = s.content ? (s.content.match(/^##/gm) || []).length || sections.length : sections.length;
    return agent(
      `You are authoring the DIAGNOSTIC PRE-QUIZ and HANDS-ON TASKS for one stage of a course on setting up Claude Code + Codex for a team.\n\n` +
      `STAGE: ${s.title} (${s.id})\nKEY CONCEPTS: ${s.concepts.join(", ")}\n\nVERIFIED CLAIMS:\n` +
      s.claims.map((c) => `- ${c}`).join("\n") +
      `\n\nDEEP CONTENT (lesson sections are 0-indexed, there are ~${sectionCount} sections):\n${s.content || "(no content yet)"}\n\n` +
      `PRE-QUIZ REQUIREMENTS:\n` +
      `- Write as many questions as needed to COVER all the key sections — no artificial limit. If a stage has 8 sections, you likely need 6-10 questions for genuine coverage.\n` +
      `- Each question MUST discriminate: someone who knows the material passes; someone who skimmed fails. "What is the best way to do X: A. wisely B. randomly C. badly D. carelessly" is REJECTED — every option must encode a real, plausible belief.\n` +
      `- Scenario-first: "Your team is doing X and Y happens — which of these explains it?", "You configure X. What is the consequence of Z?"\n` +
      `- Correct answers must be traceable to a specific claim in the VERIFIED CLAIMS or the CONTENT.\n` +
      `- sectionIndices: map each question to the section(s) it covers (0-based indices). Getting the question right → those sections start collapsed.\n\n` +
      `TASK REQUIREMENTS:\n` +
      `- 1-3 concrete hands-on tasks per stage. Real things to go do in Claude Code.\n` +
      `- Instructions must be concrete with actual commands/file paths — not 'explore the settings' but 'open ~/.claude/settings.json and add the following permission rule:...'\n` +
      `- doneWhen: one verifiable sentence ('You can run claude --version in your terminal without errors')\n`,
      { ...A, schema: PRE_SCHEMA, label: `prequiz:${s.id}`, phase: "PreQuiz" },
    );
  },
);

const finalOut = {};
stages.forEach((s, i) => {
  const mainQ = out[s.id] ?? [];
  const pre = preResults[i] ?? {};
  finalOut[s.id] = { quiz: mainQ, preQuiz: pre.preQuiz ?? [], tasks: pre.tasks ?? [] };
});
const preCounts = Object.entries(finalOut).map(([k, v]) => `${k}:pq${v.preQuiz.length}+t${v.tasks.length}`).join(" ");
log(`pre-quizzes+tasks — ${preCounts}`);
return { quizzes: finalOut };
